108
00:10:46,640 --> 00:10:47,800
Chapter 2

109
00:10:47,800 --> 00:10:48,920
PAUL

110
00:10:48,920 --> 00:10:52,760
"Come, child, the dew is falling, and it is time we went in."

111
00:10:52,760 --> 00:10:58,270
"No, no, Mamma is not rested yet, so I may run down to the spring if I like."

112
00:10:58,270 --> 00:11:04,840
And Lillian, as willful as winsome, vanished among the tall ferns where deer crouched and rabbits hid.

113
00:11:04,840 --> 00:11:14,950
Hester leisurely followed, looking as unchanged as if a day instead of twelve years had passed since her arms received the little mistress, who now ruled her like a tyrant.

114
00:11:14,950 --> 00:11:21,920
She had taken but a few steps when the child came flying back, exclaiming in an excited tone, "Oh, come quick!

115
00:11:21,920 --> 00:11:23,650
There's a man there, a dead man.

116
00:11:23,650 --> 00:11:25,450
I saw him and I'm frightened!"

117
00:11:25,450 --> 00:11:30,610
"Nonsense, child, it's one of the keepers asleep, or some stroller who has no business here.

118
00:11:30,610 --> 00:11:33,190
Take my hand and we'll see who he is."

119
00:11:33,190 --> 00:11:41,660
Somewhat reassured, Lillian led her nurse to one of the old oaks beside the path, and pointed to a figure lying half hidden in the fern.

120
00:11:41,660 --> 00:11:56,140
A slender, swarthy boy of sixteen, with curly black hair, dark brows, and thick lashes, a singularly stern mouth, and a general expression of strength and pride, which added character to his boyish face and dignified his poverty.

121
00:11:56,140 --> 00:12:05,570
His dress betrayed that, being dusty and threadbare, his shoes much worn, and his possessions contained in the little bundle on which he pillowed his head.

122
00:12:05,570 --> 00:12:13,390
He was sleeping like one quite spent with weariness, and never stirred, though Hester bent away the ferns and examined him closely.

123
00:12:13,390 --> 00:12:20,010
"He's not dead, my deary; he's asleep, poor lad, worn out with his day's tramp, I dare say."

124
00:12:20,010 --> 00:12:23,130
"I'm glad he's alive, and I wish he'd wake up.

125
00:12:23,130 --> 00:12:24,870
He's a pretty boy, isn't he?

126
00:12:24,870 --> 00:12:28,790
See what nice hands he's got, and his hair is more curly than mine.

127
00:12:28,790 --> 00:12:35,430
Make him open his eyes, Hester," commanded the little lady, whose fear had given place to interest.

128
00:12:35,430 --> 00:12:37,670
"Hush, he's stirring.

129
00:12:37,670 --> 00:12:41,350
I wonder how he got in, and what he wants," whispered Hester.

130
00:12:41,350 --> 00:12:50,000
"I'll ask him," and before her nurse could arrest her, Lillian drew a tall fern softly over the sleeper's face, laughing aloud as she did so.

131
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:57,830
The boy woke at the sound, and without stirring lay looking up at the lovely little face bent over him, as if still in a dream.

132
00:12:57,830 --> 00:13:01,120
"Bella cara," he said, in a musical voice.

133
00:13:01,120 --> 00:13:11,400
Then, as the child drew back abashed at the glance of his large, bright eyes, he seemed to wake entirely and, springing to his feet, looked at Hester with a quick, searching glance.

134
00:13:11,400 --> 00:13:19,370
Something in his face and air caused the woman to soften her tone a little, as she said gravely, "Did you wish to see any one at the Hall?"

135
00:13:19,370 --> 00:13:20,440
"Yes.

136
00:13:20,440 --> 00:13:21,890
Is Lady Trevlyn here?"

137
00:13:21,890 --> 00:13:27,450
was the boy's answer, as he stood cap in hand, with the smile fading already from his face.

138
00:13:27,450 --> 00:13:34,960
"She is, but unless your business is very urgent you had better see Parks, the keeper; we don't trouble my lady with trifles."

139
00:13:34,960 --> 00:13:41,630
"I've a note for her from Colonel Daventry; and as it is not a trifle, I'll deliver it myself, if you please."

140
00:13:41,630 --> 00:13:50,230
Hester hesitated an instant, but Lillian cried out, "Mamma is close by, come and see her," and led the way, beckoning as she ran.

141
00:13:50,230 --> 00:13:57,080
The lad followed with a composed air, and Hester brought up the rear, taking notes as she went with a woman's keen eye.

142
00:13:57,080 --> 00:14:09,010
Lady Trevlyn, a beautiful, pale woman, delicate in health and melancholy in spirit, sat on a rustic seat with a book in her hand; not reading, but musing with an absent mind.

143
00:14:09,010 --> 00:14:14,430
As the child approached, she held out her hand to welcome her, but neither smiled nor spoke.

144
00:14:14,430 --> 00:14:24,100
"Mamma, here is aâ€”a person to see you," cried Lillian, rather at a loss how to designate the stranger, whose height and gravity now awed her.

145
00:14:24,100 --> 00:14:29,100
"A note from Colonel Daventry, my lady," and with a bow the boy delivered the missive.

146
00:14:29,100 --> 00:14:33,120
Scarcely glancing at him, she opened it and read:

147
00:14:33,120 --> 00:14:34,690
My Dear Friend,

148
00:14:34,690 --> 00:14:39,800
The bearer of this, Paul Jex, has been with me some months and has served me well.

149
00:14:39,800 --> 00:14:47,470
I brought him from Paris, but he is English born, and, though friendless, prefers to remain here, even after we leave, as we do in a week.

150
00:14:47,470 --> 00:14:56,860
When I last saw you you mentioned wanting a lad to help in the garden; Paul is accustomed to that employment, though my wife used him as a sort of page in the house.

151
00:14:56,860 --> 00:15:00,800
Hoping you may be able to give him shelter, I venture to send him.

152
00:15:00,800 --> 00:15:04,950
He is honest, capable, and trustworthy in all respects.

153
00:15:04,950 --> 00:15:07,210
Pray try him, and oblige,

154
00:15:07,210 --> 00:15:08,680
Yours sincerely,

155
00:15:08,680 --> 00:15:09,200
J.

156
00:15:09,200 --> 00:15:09,570
R.

157
00:15:09,570 --> 00:15:10,780
Daventry

158
00:15:10,780 --> 00:15:21,060
"The place is still vacant, and I shall be very glad to give it to you, if you incline to take it," said Lady Trevlyn, lifting her eyes from the note and scanning the boy's face.

159
00:15:21,060 --> 00:15:24,270
"I do, madam," he answered respectfully.

160
00:15:24,270 --> 00:15:28,910
"The colonel says you are English," added the lady, in a tone of surprise.

161
00:15:28,910 --> 00:15:38,160
The boy smiled, showing a faultless set of teeth, as he replied, "I am, my lady, though just now I may not look it, being much tanned and very dusty.

162
00:15:38,160 --> 00:15:44,690
My father was an Englishman, but I've lived abroad a good deal since he died, and got foreign ways, perhaps."

163
00:15:44,690 --> 00:15:53,810
As he spoke without any accent, and looked full in her face with a pair of honest blue eyes under the dark lashes, Lady Trevlyn's momentary doubt vanished.

164
00:15:53,810 --> 00:15:55,590
"Your age, Paul?"

165
00:15:55,590 --> 00:15:57,780
"Sixteen, my lady."

166
00:15:57,780 --> 00:15:59,920
"You understand gardening?"

167
00:15:59,920 --> 00:16:01,620
"Yes, my lady."

168
00:16:01,620 --> 00:16:03,130
"And what else?"

169
00:16:03,130 --> 00:16:14,440
"I can break horses, serve at table, do errands, read aloud, ride after a young lady as groom, illuminate on parchment, train flowers, and make myself useful in any way."

170
00:16:14,440 --> 00:16:27,330
The tone, half modest, half eager, in which the boy spoke, as well as the odd list of his accomplishments, brought a smile to Lady Trevlyn's lips, and the general air of the lad prepossessed her.

171
00:16:27,330 --> 00:16:33,760
"I want Lillian to ride soon, and Roger is rather old for an escort to such a little horsewoman.

172
00:16:33,760 --> 00:16:35,700
Don't you think we might try Paul?"

173
00:16:35,700 --> 00:16:37,920
she said, turning to Hester.

174
00:16:37,920 --> 00:16:47,580
The woman gravely eyed the lad from head to foot, and shook her head, but an imploring little gesture and a glance of the handsome eyes softened her heart in spite of herself.

175
00:16:47,580 --> 00:16:53,810
"Yes, my lady, if he does well about the place, and Parks thinks he's steady enough, we might try it by-and-by."

176
00:16:53,810 --> 00:17:01,950
Lillian clapped her hands and, drawing nearer, exclaimed confidingly, as she looked up at her new groom, "I know he'll do, Mamma.

177
00:17:01,950 --> 00:17:05,670
I like him very much, and I hope you'll let him train my pony for me.

178
00:17:05,670 --> 00:17:06,980
Will you, Paul?"

179
00:17:06,980 --> 00:17:08,420
"Yes."

180
00:17:08,420 --> 00:17:17,630
As he spoke very low and hastily, the boy looked away from the eager little face before him, and a sudden flush of color crossed his dark cheek.

181
00:17:17,630 --> 00:17:22,880
Hester saw it and said within herself, "That boy has good blood in his veins.

182
00:17:22,880 --> 00:17:28,550
He's no clodhopper's son, I can tell by his hands and feet, his air and walk.

183
00:17:28,550 --> 00:17:34,040
Poor lad, it's hard for him, I'll warrant, but he's not too proud for honest work, and I like that."

184
00:17:34,040 --> 00:17:37,370
"You may stay, Paul, and we will try you for a month.

185
00:17:37,370 --> 00:17:40,920
Hester, take him to Parks and see that he is made comfortable.

186
00:17:40,920 --> 00:17:43,640
Tomorrow we will see what he can do.

187
00:17:43,640 --> 00:17:46,050
Come, darling, I am rested now."

188
00:17:46,050 --> 00:17:52,260
As she spoke, Lady Trevlyn dismissed the boy with a gracious gesture and led her little daughter away.

189
00:17:52,260 --> 00:18:04,420
Paul stood watching her, as if forgetful of his companion, till she said, rather tartly, "Young man, you'd better have thanked my lady while she was here than stare after her now it's too late.

190
00:18:04,420 --> 00:18:07,680
If you want to see Parks, you'd best come, for I'm going."

191
00:18:07,680 --> 00:18:11,410
"Is that the family tomb yonder, where you found me asleep?"

192
00:18:11,410 --> 00:18:17,450
was the unexpected reply to her speech, as the boy quietly followed her, not at all daunted by her manner.

193
00:18:17,450 --> 00:18:23,980
"Yes, and that reminds me to ask how you got in, and why you were napping there, instead of doing your errand properly?"

194
00:18:23,980 --> 00:18:33,160
"I leaped the fence and stopped to rest before presenting myself, Miss Hester" was the cool answer, accompanied by a short laugh as he confessed his trespass.

195
00:18:33,160 --> 00:18:37,100
"You look as if you'd had a long walk; where are you from?"

196
00:18:37,100 --> 00:18:38,570
"London."

197
00:18:38,570 --> 00:18:39,700
"Bless the boy!

198
00:18:39,700 --> 00:18:42,120
It's fifty miles away."

199
00:18:42,120 --> 00:18:46,460
"So my shoes show; but it's a pleasant trip in summer time."

200
00:18:46,460 --> 00:18:48,230
"But why did you walk, child!

201
00:18:48,230 --> 00:18:49,680
Had you no money?"

202
00:18:49,680 --> 00:18:54,510
"Plenty, but not for wasting on coaches, when my own stout legs could carry me.

203
00:18:54,510 --> 00:18:58,460
I took a two days' holiday and saved my money for better things."

204
00:18:58,460 --> 00:19:02,090
"I like that," said Hester, with an approving nod.

205
00:19:02,090 --> 00:19:09,240
"You'll get on, my lad, if that's your way, and I'll lend a hand, for laziness is my abomination, and one sees plenty nowadays."

206
00:19:09,240 --> 00:19:10,350
"Thank you.

207
00:19:10,350 --> 00:19:13,050
That's friendly, and I'll prove that I am grateful.

208
00:19:13,050 --> 00:19:15,940
Please tell me, is my lady ill?"

209
00:19:15,940 --> 00:19:19,480
"Always delicate since Sir Richard died."

210
00:19:19,480 --> 00:19:21,740
"How long ago was that?"

211
00:19:21,740 --> 00:19:23,760
"Ten years or more."

212
00:19:23,760 --> 00:19:26,610
"Are there no young gentlemen in the family?"

213
00:19:26,610 --> 00:19:30,880
"No, Miss Lillian is an only child, and a sweet one, bless her!"

214
00:19:30,880 --> 00:19:33,810
"A proud little lady, I should say."

215
00:19:33,810 --> 00:19:40,450
"And well she may be, for there's no better blood in England than the Trevlyns, and she's heiress to a noble fortune."

216
00:19:40,450 --> 00:19:42,600
"Is that the Trevlyn coat of arms?"

217
00:19:42,600 --> 00:19:50,800
asked the boy abruptly, pointing to a stone falcon with the motto ME AND MINE carved over the gate through which they were passing.

218
00:19:50,800 --> 00:19:51,900
"Yes.

219
00:19:51,900 --> 00:19:53,430
Why do you ask?"

220
00:19:53,430 --> 00:19:59,260
"Mere curiosity; I know something of heraldry and often paint these things for my own pleasure.

221
00:19:59,260 --> 00:20:04,860
One learns odd amusements abroad," he added, seeing an expression of surprise on the woman's face.

222
00:20:04,860 --> 00:20:08,410
"You'll have little time for such matters here.

223
00:20:08,410 --> 00:20:15,460
Come in and report yourself to the keeper, and if you'll take my advice ask no questions of him, for you'll get no answers."

224
00:20:15,460 --> 00:20:19,730
"I seldom ask questions of men, as they are not fond of gossip."

225
00:20:19,730 --> 00:20:25,210
And the boy nodded with a smile of mischievous significance as he entered the keeper's lodge.

226
00:20:25,210 --> 00:20:27,880
A sharp lad and a saucy, if he likes.

227
00:20:27,880 --> 00:20:35,540
I'll keep my eye on him, for my lady takes no more thought of such things than a child, and Lillian cares for nothing but her own will.

228
00:20:35,540 --> 00:20:39,540
He has a taking way with him, though, and knows how to flatter.

229
00:20:39,540 --> 00:20:44,890
It's well he does, poor lad, for life's a hard matter to a friendless soul like him.

230
00:20:44,890 --> 00:20:56,560
As she thought these thoughts Hester went on to the house, leaving Paul to win the good graces of the keeper, which he speedily did by assuming an utterly different manner from that he had worn with the woman.

231
00:20:56,560 --> 00:21:10,480
That night, when the boy was alone in his own room, he wrote a long letter in Italian describing the events of the day, enclosed a sketch of the falcon and motto, directed it to "Father Cosmo Carmela, Genoa,"

232
00:21:10,480 --> 00:21:24,140
and lay down to sleep, muttering, with a grim look and a heavy sigh, "So far so well; I'll not let my heart be softened by pity, or my purpose change till my promise is kept.

233
00:21:24,140 --> 00:21:27,810
Pretty child, I wish I had never seen her!"

