241
00:21:56,820 --> 00:21:58,160
Chapter 3

242
00:21:58,160 --> 00:22:00,330
SECRET SERVICE

243
00:22:00,330 --> 00:22:10,770
In a week Paul was a favorite with the household; even prudent Hester felt the charm of his presence, and owned that Lillian was happier for a young companion in her walks.

244
00:22:10,770 --> 00:22:27,060
Hitherto the child had led a solitary life, with no playmates of her own age, such being the will of my lady; therefore she welcomed Paul as a new and delightful amusement, considering him her private property and soon transferring his duties from the garden to the house.

245
00:22:27,060 --> 00:22:35,880
Satisfied of his merits, my lady yielded to Lillian's demands, and Paul was installed as page to the young lady.

246
00:22:35,880 --> 00:22:45,330
Always respectful and obedient, he never forgot his place, yet seemed unconsciously to influence all who approached him, and win the goodwill of everyone.

247
00:22:45,330 --> 00:22:54,640
My lady showed unusual interest in the lad, and Lillian openly displayed her admiration for his accomplishments and her affection for her devoted young servitor.

248
00:22:54,640 --> 00:23:05,790
Hester was much flattered by the confidence he reposed in her, for to her alone did he tell his story, and of her alone asked advice and comfort in his various small straits.

249
00:23:05,790 --> 00:23:15,490
It was as she suspected: Paul was a gentleman's son, but misfortune had robbed him of home, friends, and parents, and thrown him upon the world to shift for himself.

250
00:23:15,490 --> 00:23:21,180
This sad story touched the woman's heart, and the boy's manly spirit won respect.

251
00:23:21,180 --> 00:23:26,570
She had lost a son years ago, and her empty heart yearned over the motherless lad.

252
00:23:26,570 --> 00:23:36,760
Ashamed to confess the tender feeling, she wore her usual severe manner to him in public, but in private softened wonderfully and enjoyed the boy's regard heartily.

253
00:23:36,760 --> 00:23:38,480
"Paul, come in.

254
00:23:38,480 --> 00:23:46,300
I want to speak with you a moment," said my lady, from the long window of the library to the boy who was training vines outside.

255
00:23:46,300 --> 00:23:54,350
Dropping his tools and pulling off his hat, Paul obeyed, looking a little anxious, for the month of trial expired that day.

256
00:23:54,350 --> 00:23:58,880
Lady Trevlyn saw and answered the look with a gracious smile.

257
00:23:58,880 --> 00:24:00,360
"Have no fears.

258
00:24:00,360 --> 00:24:05,010
You are to stay if you will, for Lillian is happy and I am satisfied with you."

259
00:24:05,010 --> 00:24:06,880
"Thank you, my lady."

260
00:24:06,880 --> 00:24:11,790
And an odd glance of mingled pride and pain shone in the boy's downcast eyes.

261
00:24:11,790 --> 00:24:13,460
"That is settled, then.

262
00:24:13,460 --> 00:24:15,960
Now let me say what I called you in for.

263
00:24:15,960 --> 00:24:19,250
You spoke of being able to illuminate on parchment.

264
00:24:19,250 --> 00:24:21,750
Can you restore this old book for me?"

265
00:24:21,750 --> 00:24:26,870
She put into his hand the ancient volume Sir Richard had been reading the day he died.

266
00:24:26,870 --> 00:24:40,020
It had lain neglected in a damp nook for years till my lady discovered it, and, sad as were the associations connected with it, she desired to preserve it for the sake of the weird prophecy if nothing else.

267
00:24:40,020 --> 00:24:47,470
Paul examined it, and as he turned it to and fro in his hands it opened at the page oftenest read by its late master.

268
00:24:47,470 --> 00:24:57,040
His eye kindled as he looked, and with a quick gesture he turned as if toward the light, in truth to hide the flash of triumph that passed across his face.

269
00:24:57,040 --> 00:25:10,480
Carefully controlling his voice, he answered in a moment, as he looked up, quite composed, "Yes, my lady, I can retouch the faded colors on these margins and darken the pale ink of the Old English text.

270
00:25:10,480 --> 00:25:13,480
I like the work, and will gladly do it if you like."

271
00:25:13,480 --> 00:25:17,850
"Do it, then, but be very careful of the book while in your hands.

272
00:25:17,850 --> 00:25:23,330
Provide what is needful, and name your own price for the work," said his mistress.

273
00:25:23,330 --> 00:25:26,670
"Nay, my lady, I am already paidâ€”"

274
00:25:26,670 --> 00:25:28,240
"How so?"

275
00:25:28,240 --> 00:25:30,160
she asked, surprised.

276
00:25:30,160 --> 00:25:42,280
Paul had spoken hastily, and for an instant looked embarrassed, but answered with a sudden flush on his dark cheeks, "You have been kind to me, and I am glad to show my, gratitude in any way, my lady."

277
00:25:42,280 --> 00:25:44,310
"Let that pass, my boy.

278
00:25:44,310 --> 00:25:49,580
Do this little service for me and we will see about the recompense afterward."

279
00:25:49,580 --> 00:25:53,870
And with a smile Lady Trevlyn left him to begin his work.

280
00:25:53,870 --> 00:25:58,230
The moment the door closed behind her a total change passed over Paul.

281
00:25:58,230 --> 00:26:11,150
He shook his clenched hand after her with a gesture of menace, then tossed up the old book and caught it with an exclamation of delight, as he reopened it at the worn page and reread the inexplicable verse.

282
00:26:11,150 --> 00:26:13,710
"Another proof, another proof!

283
00:26:13,710 --> 00:26:21,210
The work goes bravely on, Father Cosmo; and boy as I am, I'll keep my word in spite of everything," he muttered.

284
00:26:21,210 --> 00:26:23,740
"What is that you'll keep, lad?"

285
00:26:23,740 --> 00:26:25,670
said a voice behind him.

286
00:26:25,670 --> 00:26:32,960
"I'll keep my word to my lady, and do my best to restore this book, Mrs. Hester," he answered, quickly recovering himself.

287
00:26:32,960 --> 00:26:36,430
"Ah, that's the last book poor Master read.

288
00:26:36,430 --> 00:26:41,820
I hid it away, but my lady found it in spite of me," said Hester, with a doleful sigh.

289
00:26:41,820 --> 00:26:43,560
"Did he die suddenly, then?"

290
00:26:43,560 --> 00:26:44,950
asked the boy.

291
00:26:44,950 --> 00:26:51,700
"Dear heart, yes; I found him dying in this room with the ink scarce dry on the letter he left for my lady.

292
00:26:51,700 --> 00:26:54,170
A mysterious business and a sad one."

293
00:26:54,170 --> 00:26:55,870
"Tell me about it.

294
00:26:55,870 --> 00:27:02,400
I like sad stories, and I already feel as if I belonged to the family, a loyal retainer as in the old times.

295
00:27:02,400 --> 00:27:08,340
While you dust the books and I rub the mold off this old cover, tell me the tale, please, Mrs. Hester."

296
00:27:08,340 --> 00:27:20,040
She shook her head, but yielded to the persuasive look and tone of the boy, telling the story more fully than she intended, for she loved talking and had come to regard Paul as her own, almost.

297
00:27:20,040 --> 00:27:21,350
"And the letter?

298
00:27:21,350 --> 00:27:22,430
What was in it?"

299
00:27:22,430 --> 00:27:25,450
asked the boy, as she paused at the catastrophe.

300
00:27:25,450 --> 00:27:28,250
"No one ever knew but my lady."

301
00:27:28,250 --> 00:27:30,370
"She destroyed it, then?"

302
00:27:30,370 --> 00:27:36,730
"I thought so, till a long time afterward, one of the lawyers came pestering me with questions, and made me ask her.

303
00:27:36,730 --> 00:27:44,810
She was ill at the time, but answered with a look I shall never forget, 'No, it's not burnt, but no one shall ever see it.'

304
00:27:44,810 --> 00:27:51,800
I dared ask no more, but I fancy she has it safe somewhere and if it's ever needed she'll bring it out.

305
00:27:51,800 --> 00:27:55,060
It was only some private matters, I fancy."

306
00:27:55,060 --> 00:27:56,740
"And the stranger?"

307
00:27:56,740 --> 00:28:00,550
"Oh, he vanished as oddly as he came, and has never been found.

308
00:28:00,550 --> 00:28:02,300
A strange story, lad.

309
00:28:02,300 --> 00:28:04,720
Keep silent, and let it rest."

310
00:28:04,720 --> 00:28:12,790
"No fear of my tattling," and the boy smiled curiously to himself as he bent over the book, polishing the brassbound cover.

311
00:28:12,790 --> 00:28:15,330
"What are you doing with that pretty white wax?"

312
00:28:15,330 --> 00:28:24,110
asked Lillian the next day, as she came upon Paul in a quiet corner of the garden and found him absorbed in some mysterious occupation.

313
00:28:24,110 --> 00:28:37,930
With a quick gesture he destroyed his work, and, banishing a momentary expression of annoyance, he answered in his accustomed tone as he began to work anew, "I am molding a little deer for you, Miss Lillian.

314
00:28:37,930 --> 00:28:42,190
See, here is a rabbit already done, and I'll soon have a stag also."

315
00:28:42,190 --> 00:28:43,790
"It's very pretty!

316
00:28:43,790 --> 00:28:49,310
How many nice things you can do, and how kind you are to think of my liking something new.

317
00:28:49,310 --> 00:28:53,340
Was this wax what you went to get this morning when you rode away so early?"

318
00:28:53,340 --> 00:28:54,980
asked the child.

319
00:28:54,980 --> 00:28:56,790
"Yes, Miss Lillian.

320
00:28:56,790 --> 00:29:00,720
I was ordered to exercise your pony and I made him useful as well.

321
00:29:00,720 --> 00:29:02,260
Would you like to try this?

322
00:29:02,260 --> 00:29:03,710
It's very easy."

323
00:29:03,710 --> 00:29:08,340
Lillian was charmed, and for several days wax modeling was her favorite play.

324
00:29:08,340 --> 00:29:16,720
Then she tired of it, and Paul invented a new amusement, smiling his inexplicable smile as he threw away the broken toys of wax.

325
00:29:16,720 --> 00:29:20,110
"You are getting pale and thin, keeping such late hours, Paul.

326
00:29:20,110 --> 00:29:28,300
Go to bed, boy, go to bed, and get your sleep early," said Hester a week afterward, with a motherly air, as Paul passed her one morning.

327
00:29:28,300 --> 00:29:30,720
"And how do you know I don't go to bed?"

328
00:29:30,720 --> 00:29:32,730
he asked, wheeling about.

329
00:29:32,730 --> 00:29:37,090
"My lady has been restless lately, and I sit up with her till she sleeps.

330
00:29:37,090 --> 00:29:45,140
As I go to my room, I see your lamp burning, and last night I got as far as your door, meaning to speak to you, but didn't, thinking you'd take it amiss.

331
00:29:45,140 --> 00:29:48,350
But really you are the worse for late hours, child."

332
00:29:48,350 --> 00:29:51,850
"I shall soon finish restoring the book, and then I'll sleep.

333
00:29:51,850 --> 00:29:53,370
I hope I don't disturb you.

334
00:29:53,370 --> 00:29:57,200
I have to grind my colors, and often make more noise than I mean to."

335
00:29:57,200 --> 00:30:07,310
Paul fixed his eyes sharply on the woman as he spoke, but she seemed unconscious of it, and turned to go on, saying indifferently, "Oh, that's the odd sound, is it?

336
00:30:07,310 --> 00:30:12,560
No, it doesn't trouble me, so grind away, and make an end of it as soon as may be."

337
00:30:12,560 --> 00:30:23,050
An anxious fold in the boy's forehead smoothed itself away as he left her, saying to himself with a sigh of relief, "A narrow escape; it's well I keep the door locked."

338
00:30:23,050 --> 00:30:29,400
The boy's light burned no more after that, and Hester was content till a new worry came to trouble her.

339
00:30:29,400 --> 00:30:37,210
On her way to her room late one night, she saw a tall shadow flit down one of the side corridors that branched from the main one.

340
00:30:37,210 --> 00:30:45,740
For a moment she was startled, but, being a woman of courage, she followed noiselessly, till the shadow seemed to vanish in the gloom of the great hall.

341
00:30:45,740 --> 00:30:51,930
"If the house ever owned a ghost I'd say that's it, but it never did, so I suspect some deviltry.

342
00:30:51,930 --> 00:30:53,140
I'll step to Paul.

343
00:30:53,140 --> 00:30:54,730
He's not asleep, I dare say.

344
00:30:54,730 --> 00:30:59,240
He's a brave and a sensible lad, and with him I'll quietly search the house."

345
00:30:59,240 --> 00:31:04,240
Away she went, more nervous than she would own, and tapped at the boy's door.

346
00:31:04,240 --> 00:31:10,590
No one answered, and, seeing that it was ajar, Hester whisked in so hurriedly that her candle went out.

347
00:31:10,590 --> 00:31:18,580
With an impatient exclamation at her carelessness she glided to the bed, drew the curtain, and put forth her hand to touch the sleeper.

348
00:31:18,580 --> 00:31:20,170
The bed was empty.

349
00:31:20,170 --> 00:31:26,240
A disagreeable thrill shot through her, as she assured herself of the fact by groping along the narrow bed.

350
00:31:26,240 --> 00:31:34,410
Standing in the shadow of the curtain, she stared about the dusky room, in which objects were visible by the light of a new moon.

351
00:31:34,410 --> 00:31:37,290
"Lord bless me, what is the boy about!

352
00:31:37,290 --> 00:31:46,340
I do believe it was him I saw in theâ€”" She got no further in her mental exclamation for the sound of light approaching footsteps neared her.

353
00:31:46,340 --> 00:31:57,620
Slipping around the bed she waited in the shadow, and a moment after Paul appeared, looking pale and ghostly, with dark, disheveled hair, wide-open eyes, and a cloak thrown over his shoulders.

354
00:31:57,620 --> 00:32:02,970
Without a pause he flung it off, laid himself in bed, and seemed to sleep at once.

355
00:32:02,970 --> 00:32:04,140
"Paul!

356
00:32:04,140 --> 00:32:05,050
Paul!"

357
00:32:05,050 --> 00:32:10,320
whispered Hester, shaking him, after a pause of astonishment at the whole proceeding.

358
00:32:10,320 --> 00:32:12,140
"Hey, what is it?"

359
00:32:12,140 --> 00:32:14,850
And he sat up, looking drowsily about him.

360
00:32:14,850 --> 00:32:16,980
"Come, come, no tricks, boy.

361
00:32:16,980 --> 00:32:21,130
What are you doing, trailing about the house at this hour and in such trim?"

362
00:32:21,130 --> 00:32:23,350
"Why, Hester, is it you?"

363
00:32:23,350 --> 00:32:27,730
he exclaimed with a laugh, as he shook off her grip and looked up at her in surprise.

364
00:32:27,730 --> 00:32:29,900
"Yes, and well it is me.

365
00:32:29,900 --> 00:32:33,990
If it had been any of those silly girls, the house would have been roused by this time.

366
00:32:33,990 --> 00:32:38,410
What mischief is afoot that you leave your bed and play ghost in this wild fashion?"

367
00:32:38,410 --> 00:32:39,890
"Leave my bed!

368
00:32:39,890 --> 00:32:45,050
Why, my good soul, I haven't stirred, but have been dreaming with all my might these two hours.

369
00:32:45,050 --> 00:32:46,750
What do you mean, Hester?"

370
00:32:46,750 --> 00:32:51,510
She told him as she relit her lamp, and stood eyeing him sharply the while.

371
00:32:51,510 --> 00:33:01,000
When she finished he was silent a minute, then said, looking half vexed and half ashamed, "I see how it is, and I'm glad you alone have found me out.

372
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:04,240
I walk in my sleep sometimes, Hester, that's the truth.

373
00:33:04,240 --> 00:33:08,750
I thought I'd got over it, but it's come back, you see, and I'm sorry for it.

374
00:33:08,750 --> 00:33:10,020
Don't be troubled.

375
00:33:10,020 --> 00:33:12,850
I never do any mischief or come to any harm.

376
00:33:12,850 --> 00:33:15,730
I just take a quiet promenade and march back to bed again.

377
00:33:15,730 --> 00:33:17,400
Did I frighten you?"

378
00:33:17,400 --> 00:33:19,870
"Just a trifle, but it's nothing.

379
00:33:19,870 --> 00:33:27,710
Poor lad, you'll have to have a bedfellow or be locked up; it's dangerous to go roaming about in this way," said Hester anxiously.

380
00:33:27,710 --> 00:33:31,960
"It won't last long, for I'll get more tired and then I shall sleep sounder.

381
00:33:31,960 --> 00:33:35,890
Don't tell anyone, please, else they'll laugh at me, and that's not pleasant.

382
00:33:35,890 --> 00:33:41,670
I don't mind your knowing for you seem almost like a mother, and I thank you for it with all my heart."

383
00:33:41,670 --> 00:33:45,980
He held out his hand with the look that was irresistible to Hester.

384
00:33:45,980 --> 00:33:55,080
Remembering only that he was a motherless boy, she stroked the curly hair off his forehead, and kissed him, with the thought of her own son warm at her heart.

385
00:33:55,080 --> 00:33:56,320
"Good night, dear.

386
00:33:56,320 --> 00:34:01,830
I'll say nothing, but give you something that will ensure quiet sleep hereafter."

387
00:34:01,830 --> 00:34:12,400
With that she left him, but would have been annoyed could she have seen the convulsion of boyish merriment which took possession of him alone, for he laughed till the tears ran down his cheeks.

