392
00:34:32,500 --> 00:34:33,860
Chapter 4

393
00:34:33,860 --> 00:34:35,350
VANISHED

394
00:34:35,350 --> 00:34:48,930
He's a handsome lad, and one any woman might be proud to call her son," said Hester to Bedford, the stately butler, as they lingered at the hall door one autumn morning to watch their young lady's departure on her daily ride.

395
00:34:48,930 --> 00:34:58,530
"You are right, Mrs. Hester, he's a fine lad, and yet he seems above his place, though he does look the very picture of a lady's groom," replied Bedford approvingly.

396
00:34:58,530 --> 00:35:08,510
So he did, as he stood holding the white pony of his little mistress, for the boy gave an air to whatever he wore and looked like a gentleman even in his livery.

397
00:35:08,510 --> 00:35:19,750
The dark-blue coat with silver buttons, the silver band about his hat, his white-topped boots and bright spurs, spotless gloves, and tightly drawn belt were all in perfect order,

398
00:35:19,750 --> 00:35:27,840
all becoming, and his handsome, dark face caused many a susceptible maid to blush and simper as they passed him.

399
00:35:27,840 --> 00:35:40,070
"Gentleman Paul," as the servants called him, was rather lofty and reserved among his mates, but they liked him nonetheless, for Hester had dropped hints of his story and quite a little romance had sprung up about him.

400
00:35:40,070 --> 00:35:48,340
He stood leaning against the docile creature, sunk in thought, and quite unconscious of the watchers and whisperers close by.

401
00:35:48,340 --> 00:35:57,920
But as Lillian appeared he woke up, attended to his duties like a well-trained groom, and lingered over his task as if he liked it.

402
00:35:57,920 --> 00:36:07,740
Down the avenue he rode behind her, but as they turned into a shady lane Lillian beckoned, saying, in the imperious tone habitual to her, "Ride near me.

403
00:36:07,740 --> 00:36:09,150
I wish to talk."

404
00:36:09,150 --> 00:36:19,810
Paul obeyed, and amused her with the chat she liked till they reached a hazel copse; here he drew rein, and, leaping down, gathered a handful of ripe nuts for her.

405
00:36:19,810 --> 00:36:21,060
"How nice.

406
00:36:21,060 --> 00:36:25,970
Let us rest a minute here, and while I eat a few, please pull some of those flowers for Mamma.

407
00:36:25,970 --> 00:36:30,180
She likes a wild nosegay better than any I can bring her from the garden."

408
00:36:30,180 --> 00:36:41,340
Lillian ate her nuts till Paul came to her with a hatful of late flowers and, standing by her, held the impromptu basket while she made up a bouquet to suit her taste.

409
00:36:41,340 --> 00:36:51,410
"You shall have a posy, too; I like you to wear one in your buttonhole as the ladies' grooms do in the Park," said the child, settling a scarlet poppy in the blue coat.

410
00:36:51,410 --> 00:36:57,070
"Thanks, Miss Lillian, I'll wear your colors with all my heart, especially today, for it is my birthday."

411
00:36:57,070 --> 00:37:02,760
And Paul looked up at the blooming little face with unusual softness in his keen blue eyes.

412
00:37:02,760 --> 00:37:04,090
"Is it?

413
00:37:04,090 --> 00:37:07,550
Why, then, you're seventeen; almost a man, aren't you?"

414
00:37:07,550 --> 00:37:11,650
"Yes, thank heaven," muttered the boy, half to himself.

415
00:37:11,650 --> 00:37:13,230
"I wish I was as old.

416
00:37:13,230 --> 00:37:15,370
I shan't be in my teens till autumn.

417
00:37:15,370 --> 00:37:21,050
I must give you something, Paul, because I like you very much, and you are always doing kind things for me.

418
00:37:21,050 --> 00:37:21,860
What shall it be?"

419
00:37:21,860 --> 00:37:27,370
And the child held out her hand with a cordial look and gesture that touched the boy.

420
00:37:27,370 --> 00:37:42,160
With one of the foreign fashions which sometimes appeared when he forgot himself, he kissed the small hand, saying impulsively, "My dear little mistress, I want nothing but your goodwillâ€”and your forgiveness," he added, under his breath.

421
00:37:42,160 --> 00:37:46,170
"You have that already, Paul, and I shall find something to add to it.

422
00:37:46,170 --> 00:37:47,590
But what is that?"

423
00:37:47,590 --> 00:37:53,270
And she laid hold of a little locket which had slipped into sight as Paul bent forward in his salute.

424
00:37:53,270 --> 00:38:01,340
He thrust it back, coloring so deeply that the child observed it, and exclaimed, with a mischievous laugh, "It is your sweetheart, Paul.

425
00:38:01,340 --> 00:38:06,840
I heard Bessy, my maid, tell Hester she was sure you had one because you took no notice of them.

426
00:38:06,840 --> 00:38:07,970
Let me see it.

427
00:38:07,970 --> 00:38:10,020
Is she pretty?"

428
00:38:10,020 --> 00:38:13,230
"Very pretty," answered the boy, without showing the picture.

429
00:38:13,230 --> 00:38:15,070
"Do you like her very much?"

430
00:38:15,070 --> 00:38:18,840
questioned Lillian, getting interested in the little romance.

431
00:38:18,840 --> 00:38:22,620
"Very much," and Paul's black eyelashes fell.

432
00:38:22,620 --> 00:38:25,760
"Would you die for her, as they say in the old songs?"

433
00:38:25,760 --> 00:38:28,020
asked the girl, melodramatically.

434
00:38:28,020 --> 00:38:32,090
"Yes, Miss Lillian, or live for her, which is harder."

435
00:38:32,090 --> 00:38:38,160
"Dear me, how very nice it must be to have anyone care for one so much," said the child innocently.

436
00:38:38,160 --> 00:38:40,700
"I wonder if anybody ever will for me?"

437
00:38:40,700 --> 00:38:48,380
"Love comes to all soon or late, And maketh gay or sad; For every bird will find its mate, And every lass a lad,"

438
00:38:48,380 --> 00:38:54,510
sang Paul, quoting one of Hester's songs, and looking relieved that Lillian's thoughts had strayed from him.

439
00:38:54,510 --> 00:38:56,620
But he was mistaken.

440
00:38:56,620 --> 00:38:59,730
"Shall you marry this sweetheart of yours someday?"

441
00:38:59,730 --> 00:39:04,190
asked Lillian, turning to him with a curious yet wistful look.

442
00:39:04,190 --> 00:39:05,890
"Perhaps."

443
00:39:05,890 --> 00:39:15,490
"You look as if there was no 'perhaps' about it," said the child, quick to read the kindling of the eye and the change in the voice that accompanied the boy's reply.

444
00:39:15,490 --> 00:39:21,550
"She is very young and I must wait, and while I wait many things may happen to part us."

445
00:39:21,550 --> 00:39:23,530
"Is she a lady?"

446
00:39:23,530 --> 00:39:28,110
"Yes, a wellborn, lovely little lady, and I'll marry her if I live."

447
00:39:28,110 --> 00:39:36,220
Paul spoke with a look of decision, and a proud lift of the head that contrasted curiously with the badge of servitude he wore.

448
00:39:36,220 --> 00:39:45,630
Lillian felt this, and asked, with a sudden shyness coming over her, "But you are a gentleman, and so no one will mind even if you are not rich."

449
00:39:45,630 --> 00:39:47,490
"How do you know what I am?"

450
00:39:47,490 --> 00:39:49,210
he asked quickly.

451
00:39:49,210 --> 00:39:56,170
"I heard Hester tell the housekeeper that you were not what you seemed, and one day she hoped you'd get your right place again.

452
00:39:56,170 --> 00:40:03,140
I asked Mamma about it, and she said she would not let me be with you so much if you were not a fit companion for me.

453
00:40:03,140 --> 00:40:09,210
I was not to speak of it, but she means to be your friend and help you by-and-by."

454
00:40:09,210 --> 00:40:10,760
"Does she?"

455
00:40:10,760 --> 00:40:24,410
And the boy laughed an odd, short laugh that jarred on Lillian's ear and made her say reprovingly, "You are proud, I know, but you'll let us help you because we like to do it, and I have no brother to share my money with."

456
00:40:24,410 --> 00:40:27,080
"Would you like one, or a sister?"

457
00:40:27,080 --> 00:40:30,920
asked Paul, looking straight into her face with his piercing eyes.

458
00:40:30,920 --> 00:40:32,470
"Yes, indeed!

459
00:40:32,470 --> 00:40:36,030
I long for someone to be with me and love me, as Mamma can't."

460
00:40:36,030 --> 00:40:44,520
"Would you be willing to share everything with another personâ€”perhaps have to give them a great many things you like and now have all to yourself?"

461
00:40:44,520 --> 00:40:46,190
"I think I should.

462
00:40:46,190 --> 00:40:54,160
I'm selfish, I know, because everyone pets and spoils me, but if I loved a person dearly I'd give up anything to them.

463
00:40:54,160 --> 00:40:57,330
Indeed I would, Paul, pray believe me."

464
00:40:57,330 --> 00:41:02,160
She spoke earnestly, and leaned on his shoulder as if to enforce her words.

465
00:41:02,160 --> 00:41:14,940
The boy's arm stole around the little figure in the saddle, and a beautiful bright smile broke over his face as he answered warmly, "I do believe it, dear, and it makes me happy to hear you say so.

466
00:41:14,940 --> 00:41:21,860
Don't be afraid, I'm your equal, but I'll not forget that you are my little mistress till I can change from groom to gentleman."

467
00:41:21,860 --> 00:41:32,020
He added the last sentence as he withdrew his arm, for Lillian had shrunk a little and blushed with surprise, not anger, at this first breach of respect on the part of her companion.

468
00:41:32,020 --> 00:41:38,460
Both were silent for a moment, Paul looking down and Lillian busy with her nosegay.

469
00:41:38,460 --> 00:41:43,350
She spoke first, assuming an air of satisfaction as she surveyed her work.

470
00:41:43,350 --> 00:41:49,260
"That will please Mamma, I'm sure, and make her quite forget my naughty prank of yesterday.

471
00:41:49,260 --> 00:41:54,350
Do you know I offended her dreadfully by peeping into the gold case she wears on her neck?

472
00:41:54,350 --> 00:41:57,030
She was asleep and I was sitting by her.

473
00:41:57,030 --> 00:42:01,690
In her sleep she pulled it out and said something about a letter and Papa.

474
00:42:01,690 --> 00:42:15,670
I wanted to see Papa's face, for I never did, because the big picture of him is gone from the gallery where the others are, so I peeped into the case when she let it drop and was so disappointed to find nothing but a key."

475
00:42:15,670 --> 00:42:16,930
"A key!

476
00:42:16,930 --> 00:42:18,310
What sort of a key?"

477
00:42:18,310 --> 00:42:20,530
cried Paul in an eager tone.

478
00:42:20,530 --> 00:42:26,160
"Oh, a little silver one like the key of my piano, or the black cabinet.

479
00:42:26,160 --> 00:42:29,460
She woke and was very angry to find me meddling."

480
00:42:29,460 --> 00:42:31,220
"What did it belong to?"

481
00:42:31,220 --> 00:42:32,470
asked Paul.

482
00:42:32,470 --> 00:42:41,330
"Her treasure box, she said, but I don't know where or what that is, and I dare not ask any more, for she forbade my speaking to her about it.

483
00:42:41,330 --> 00:42:42,430
Poor Mamma!

484
00:42:42,430 --> 00:42:45,240
I'm always troubling her in some way or other."

485
00:42:45,240 --> 00:42:50,660
With a penitent sigh, Lillian tied up her flowers and handed them to Paul to carry.

486
00:42:50,660 --> 00:42:53,590
As she did so, the change in his face struck her.

487
00:42:53,590 --> 00:42:56,600
"How grim and old you look," she exclaimed.

488
00:42:56,600 --> 00:42:58,980
"Have I said anything that troubles you?"

489
00:42:58,980 --> 00:43:00,560
"No, Miss Lillian.

490
00:43:00,560 --> 00:43:02,290
I'm only thinking."

491
00:43:02,290 --> 00:43:09,740
"Then I wish you wouldn't think, for you get a great wrinkle in your forehead, your eyes grow almost black, and your mouth looks fierce.

492
00:43:09,740 --> 00:43:17,690
You are a very odd person, Paul; one minute as gay as any boy, and the next as grave and stern as a man with a deal of work to do."

493
00:43:17,690 --> 00:43:22,450
"I have got a deal of work to do, so no wonder I look old and grim."

494
00:43:22,450 --> 00:43:24,380
"What work, Paul?"

495
00:43:24,380 --> 00:43:27,280
"To make my fortune and win my lady."

496
00:43:27,280 --> 00:43:35,610
When Paul spoke in that tone and wore that look, Lillian felt as if they had changed places, and he was the master and she the servant.

497
00:43:35,610 --> 00:43:47,210
She wondered over this in her childish mind, but proud and willful as she was, she liked it, and obeyed him with unusual meekness when he suggested that it was time to return.

498
00:43:47,210 --> 00:43:57,220
As he rode silently beside her, she stole covert glances at him from under her wide hat brim, and studied his unconscious face as she had never done before.

499
00:43:57,220 --> 00:44:07,830
His lips moved now and then but uttered no audible sound, his black brows were knit, and once his hand went to his breast as if he thought of the little sweetheart whose picture lay there.

500
00:44:07,830 --> 00:44:10,260
He's got a trouble.

501
00:44:10,260 --> 00:44:13,390
I wish he'd tell me and let me help him if I can.

502
00:44:13,390 --> 00:44:21,180
I'll make him show me that miniature someday, for I'm interested in that girl, thought Lillian with a pensive sigh.

503
00:44:21,180 --> 00:44:32,150
As he held his hand for her little foot in dismounting her at the hall door, Paul seemed to have shaken off his grave mood, for he looked up and smiled at her with his blithest expression.

504
00:44:32,150 --> 00:44:45,710
But Lillian appeared to be the thoughtful one now and with an air of dignity, very pretty and becoming, thanked her young squire in a stately manner and swept into the house, looking tall and womanly in her flowing skirts.

505
00:44:45,710 --> 00:44:57,680
Paul laughed as he glanced after her and, flinging himself onto his horse, rode away to the stables at a reckless pace, as if to work off some emotion for which he could find no other vent.

506
00:44:57,680 --> 00:45:01,520
"Here's a letter for you, lad, all the way from some place in Italy.

507
00:45:01,520 --> 00:45:03,030
Who do you know there?"

508
00:45:03,030 --> 00:45:05,500
said Bedford, as the boy came back.

509
00:45:05,500 --> 00:45:17,940
With a hasty "Thank you," Paul caught the letter and darted away to his own room, there to tear it open and, after reading a single line, to drop into a chair as if he had received a sudden blow.

510
00:45:17,940 --> 00:45:27,280
Growing paler and paler he read on, and when the letter fell from his hands he exclaimed, in a tone of despair, "How could he die at such a time!"

511
00:45:27,280 --> 00:45:34,930
For an hour the boy sat thinking intently, with locked door, curtained window, and several papers strewn before him.

512
00:45:34,930 --> 00:45:44,960
Letters, memoranda, plans, drawings, and bits of parchment, all of which he took from a small locked portfolio always worn about him.

513
00:45:44,960 --> 00:45:52,070
Over these he pored with a face in which hope, despondency, resolve, and regret alternated rapidly.

514
00:45:52,070 --> 00:45:59,640
Taking the locket out he examined a ring which lay in one side, and the childish face which smiled on him from the other.

515
00:45:59,640 --> 00:46:05,810
His eyes filled as he locked and put it by, saying tenderly, "Dear little heart!

516
00:46:05,810 --> 00:46:08,940
I'll not forget or desert her whatever happens.

517
00:46:08,940 --> 00:46:12,440
Time must help me, and to time I must leave my work.

518
00:46:12,440 --> 00:46:14,650
One more attempt and then I'm off."

519
00:46:14,650 --> 00:46:19,770
"I'll go to bed now, Hester; but while you get my things ready I'll take a turn in the corridor.

520
00:46:19,770 --> 00:46:21,670
The air will refresh me."

521
00:46:21,670 --> 00:46:31,920
As she spoke, Lady Trevlyn drew her wrapper about her and paced softly down the long hall lighted only by fitful gleams of moonlight and the ruddy glow of the fire.

522
00:46:31,920 --> 00:46:45,680
At the far end was the state chamber, never used now, and never visited except by Hester, who occasionally went in to dust and air it, and my lady, who always passed the anniversary of Sir Richard's death alone there.

523
00:46:45,680 --> 00:46:56,640
The gallery was very dark, and she seldom went farther than the last window in her restless walks, but as she now approached she was startled to see a streak of yellow light under the door.

524
00:46:56,640 --> 00:47:01,600
She kept the key herself and neither she nor Hester had been there that day.

525
00:47:01,600 --> 00:47:10,980
A cold shiver passed over her for, as she looked, the shadow of a foot darkened the light for a moment and vanished as if someone had noiselessly passed.

526
00:47:10,980 --> 00:47:15,920
Obeying a sudden impulse, my lady sprang forward and tried to open the door.

527
00:47:15,920 --> 00:47:23,070
It was locked, but as her hand turned the silver knob a sound as if a drawer softly closed met her ear.

528
00:47:23,070 --> 00:47:28,100
She stooped to the keyhole but it was dark, a key evidently being in the lock.

529
00:47:28,100 --> 00:47:35,460
She drew back and flew to her room, snatched the key from her dressing table, and, bidding Hester follow, returned to the hall.

530
00:47:35,460 --> 00:47:38,030
"What is it, my lady?"

531
00:47:38,030 --> 00:47:41,520
cried the woman, alarmed at the agitation of her mistress.

532
00:47:41,520 --> 00:47:44,640
"A light, a sound, a shadow in the state chamber.

533
00:47:44,640 --> 00:47:45,600
Come quick!"

534
00:47:45,600 --> 00:47:51,510
cried Lady Trevlyn, adding, as she pointed to the door, "There, there, the light shines underneath.

535
00:47:51,510 --> 00:47:52,780
Do you see it?"

536
00:47:52,780 --> 00:47:56,530
"No, my lady, it's dark," returned Hester.

537
00:47:56,530 --> 00:48:05,810
It was, but never pausing my lady thrust in the key, and to her surprise it turned, the door flew open, and the dim, still room was before them.

538
00:48:05,810 --> 00:48:20,530
Hester boldly entered, and while her mistress slowly followed, she searched the room, looking behind the tall screen by the hearth, up the wide chimney, in the great wardrobe, and under the ebony cabinet, where all the relics of Sir Richard were kept.

539
00:48:20,530 --> 00:48:25,840
Nothing appeared, not even a mouse, and Hester turned to my lady with an air of relief.

540
00:48:25,840 --> 00:48:33,630
But her mistress pointed to the bed shrouded in dark velvet hangings, and whispered breathlessly, "You forgot to look there."

541
00:48:33,630 --> 00:48:43,520
Hester had not forgotten, but in spite of her courage and good sense she shrank a little from looking at the spot where she had last seen her master's dead face.

542
00:48:43,520 --> 00:48:51,190
She believed the light and sound to be phantoms of my lady's distempered fancy, and searched merely to satisfy her.

543
00:48:51,190 --> 00:48:59,120
The mystery of Sir Richard's death still haunted the minds of all who remembered it, and even Hester felt a superstitious dread of that room.

544
00:48:59,120 --> 00:49:07,340
With a nervous laugh she looked under the bed and, drawing back the heavy curtains, said soothingly, "You see, my lady, there's nothing there."

545
00:49:07,340 --> 00:49:22,260
But the words died on her lips, for, as the pale glimmer of the candle pierced the gloom of that funeral couch, both saw a face upon the pillow: a pale face framed in dark hair and beard, with closed eyes and the stony look the dead wear.

546
00:49:22,260 --> 00:49:36,070
A loud, long shriek that roused the house broke from Lady Trevlyn as she fell senseless at the bedside, and dropping both curtain and candle Hester caught up her mistress and fled from the haunted room, locking the door behind her.

547
00:49:36,070 --> 00:49:44,680
In a moment a dozen servants were about them, and into their astonished ears Hester poured her story while vainly trying to restore her lady.

548
00:49:44,680 --> 00:49:54,780
Great was the dismay and intense the unwillingness of anyone to obey when Hester ordered the men to search the room again, for she was the first to regain her self-possession.

549
00:49:54,780 --> 00:49:56,390
"Where's Paul?

550
00:49:56,390 --> 00:50:01,620
He's the heart of a man, boy though he is," she said angrily as the men hung back.

551
00:50:01,620 --> 00:50:03,530
"He's not here.

552
00:50:03,530 --> 00:50:03,910
Lord!

553
00:50:03,910 --> 00:50:10,090
Maybe it was him a-playing tricks, though it ain't like him," cried Bessy, Lillian's little maid.

554
00:50:10,090 --> 00:50:12,460
"No, it can't be him, for I locked him in myself.

555
00:50:12,460 --> 00:50:16,380
He walks in his sleep sometimes, and I was afraid he'd startle my lady.

556
00:50:16,380 --> 00:50:20,690
Let him sleep; this would only excite him and set him to marching again.

557
00:50:20,690 --> 00:50:25,040
Follow me, Bedford and James, I'm not afraid of ghosts or rogues."

558
00:50:25,040 --> 00:50:33,340
With a face that belied her words Hester led the way to the awful room, and flinging back the curtain resolutely looked in.

559
00:50:33,340 --> 00:50:40,900
The bed was empty, but on the pillow was plainly visible the mark of a head and a single scarlet stain, as of blood.

560
00:50:40,900 --> 00:50:52,110
At that sight Hester turned pale and caught the butler's arm, whispering with a shudder, "Do you remember the night we put him in his coffin, the drop of blood that fell from his white lips?

561
00:50:52,110 --> 00:50:54,250
Sir Richard has been here."

562
00:50:54,250 --> 00:50:56,560
"Good Lord, ma'am, don't say that!

563
00:50:56,560 --> 00:51:02,660
We can never rest in our beds if such things are to happen," gasped Bedford, backing to the door.

564
00:51:02,660 --> 00:51:18,750
"It's no use to look, we've found all we shall find so go your ways and tell no one of this," said the woman in a gloomy tone, and, having assured herself that the windows were fast, Hester locked the room and ordered everyone but Bedford and the housekeeper to bed.

565
00:51:18,750 --> 00:51:31,280
"Do you sit outside my lady's door till morning," she said to the butler, "and you, Mrs. Price, help me to tend my poor lady, for if I'm not mistaken this night's work will bring on the old trouble."

566
00:51:31,280 --> 00:51:43,000
Morning came, and with it a new alarm; for, though his door was fast locked and no foothold for even a sparrow outside the window, Paul's room was empty, and the boy nowhere to be found.

567
