571
00:52:00,170 --> 00:52:01,430
Chapter 5

572
00:52:01,430 --> 00:52:03,190
A HERO

573
00:52:03,190 --> 00:52:15,470
Four years had passed, and Lillian was fast blooming into a lovely woman: proud and willful as ever, but very charming, and already a belle in the little world where she still reigned a queen.

574
00:52:15,470 --> 00:52:30,230
Owing to her mother's ill health, she was allowed more freedom than is usually permitted to an English girl of her age; and, during the season, often went into company with a friend of Lady Trevlyn's who was chaperoning two young daughters of her own.

575
00:52:30,230 --> 00:52:39,960
To the world Lillian seemed a gay, free-hearted girl; and no one, not even her mother, knew how well she remembered and how much she missed the lost Paul.

576
00:52:39,960 --> 00:52:45,370
No tidings of him had ever come, and no trace of him was found after his flight.

577
00:52:45,370 --> 00:52:52,620
Nothing was missed, he went without his wages, and no reason could be divined for his departure except the foreign letter.

578
00:52:52,620 --> 00:52:59,360
Bedford remembered it, but forgot what postmark it bore, for he had only been able to decipher "Italy."

579
00:52:59,360 --> 00:53:09,970
My lady made many inquiries and often spoke of him; but when month after month passed and no news came, she gave him up, and on Lillian's account feigned to forget him.

580
00:53:09,970 --> 00:53:23,610
Contrary to Hester's fear, she did not seem the worse for the nocturnal fright, but evidently connected the strange visitor with Paul, or, after a day or two of nervous exhaustion, returned to her usual state of health.

581
00:53:23,610 --> 00:53:34,800
Hester had her own misgivings, but, being forbidden to allude to the subject, she held her peace, after emphatically declaring that Paul would yet appear to set her mind at rest.

582
00:53:34,800 --> 00:53:37,660
"Lillian, Lillian, I've such news for you!

583
00:53:37,660 --> 00:53:41,520
Come and hear a charming little romance, and prepare to see the hero of it!"

584
00:53:41,520 --> 00:53:48,310
cried Maud Churchill, rushing into her friend's pretty boudoir one day in the height of the season.

585
00:53:48,310 --> 00:53:57,870
Lillian lay on a couch, rather languid after a ball, and listlessly begged Maud to tell her story, for she was dying to be amused.

586
00:53:57,870 --> 00:54:02,520
"Well my, dear, just listen and you'll be as enthusiastic as I am," cried Maud.

587
00:54:02,520 --> 00:54:10,390
And throwing her bonnet on one chair, her parasol on another, and her gloves anywhere, she settled herself on the couch and began: "

588
00:54:10,390 --> 00:54:20,230
You remember reading in the papers, some time ago, that fine account of the young man who took part in the Italian revolution and did that heroic thing with the bombshell?"

589
00:54:20,230 --> 00:54:21,860
"Yes, what of him?"

590
00:54:21,860 --> 00:54:24,210
asked Lillian, sitting up.

591
00:54:24,210 --> 00:54:27,350
"He is my hero, and we are to see him tonight."

592
00:54:27,350 --> 00:54:28,790
"Go on, go on!

593
00:54:28,790 --> 00:54:31,910
Tell all, and tell it quickly," she cried.

594
00:54:31,910 --> 00:54:38,700
"You know the officers were sitting somewhere, holding a council, while the city (I forget the name) was being bombarded,

595
00:54:38,700 --> 00:54:48,680
and how a shell came into the midst of them, how they sat paralyzed, expecting it to burst, and how this young man caught it up and ran out with it, risking his own life to save theirs?"

596
00:54:48,680 --> 00:54:50,910
"Yes, yes, I remember!"

597
00:54:50,910 --> 00:54:54,460
And Lillian's listless face kindled at the recollection.

598
00:54:54,460 --> 00:55:01,840
"Well, an Englishman who was there was so charmed by the act that, finding the young man was poor and an orphan, he adopted him.

599
00:55:01,840 --> 00:55:08,670
Mr. Talbot was old, and lonely, and rich, and when he died, a year after, he left his name and fortune to this Paolo."

600
00:55:08,670 --> 00:55:10,510
"I'm glad, I'm glad!"

601
00:55:10,510 --> 00:55:13,740
cried Lillian, clapping her hands with a joyful face.

602
00:55:13,740 --> 00:55:16,020
"How romantic and charming it is!"

603
00:55:16,020 --> 00:55:17,240
"Isn't it?

604
00:55:17,240 --> 00:55:20,740
But, my dear creature, the most romantic part is to come.

605
00:55:20,740 --> 00:55:25,710
Young Talbot served in the war, and then came to England to take possession of his property.

606
00:55:25,710 --> 00:55:31,930
It's somewhere down in Kent, a fine place and good income, all his; and he deserves it.

607
00:55:31,930 --> 00:55:37,300
Mamma heard a deal about him from Mrs. Langdon, who knew old Talbot and has seen the young man.

608
00:55:37,300 --> 00:55:43,650
Of course all the girls are wild to behold him, for he is very handsome and accomplished, and a gentleman by birth.

609
00:55:43,650 --> 00:55:55,810
But the dreadful part is that he is already betrothed to a lovely Greek girl, who came over at the same time, and is living in London with a companion; quite elegantly, Mrs. Langdon says, for she called and was charmed.

610
00:55:55,810 --> 00:56:03,220
This girl has been seen by some of our gentlemen friends, and they already rave about the 'fair Helene,' for that's her name."

611
00:56:03,220 --> 00:56:08,260
Here Maud was forced to stop for breath, and Lillian had a chance to question her.

612
00:56:08,260 --> 00:56:09,810
"How old is she?"

613
00:56:09,810 --> 00:56:12,890
"About eighteen or nineteen, they say."

614
00:56:12,890 --> 00:56:14,540
"Very pretty?"

615
00:56:14,540 --> 00:56:18,670
"Ravishing, regularly Greek and divine, Fred Raleigh says."

616
00:56:18,670 --> 00:56:20,560
"When is she to be married?"

617
00:56:20,560 --> 00:56:24,060
"Don't know; when Talbot gets settled, I fancy."

618
00:56:24,060 --> 00:56:25,110
"And he?

619
00:56:25,110 --> 00:56:27,220
Is he as charming as she?"

620
00:56:27,220 --> 00:56:29,610
"Quite, I'm told.

621
00:56:29,610 --> 00:56:34,610
He's just of age, and is, in appearance as in everything else, a hero of romance."

622
00:56:34,610 --> 00:56:38,570
"How came your mother to secure him for tonight?"

623
00:56:38,570 --> 00:56:42,190
"Mrs. Langdon is dying to make a lion of him, and begged to bring him.

624
00:56:42,190 --> 00:56:46,760
He is very indifferent on such things and seems intent on his own affairs.

625
00:56:46,760 --> 00:56:57,130
Is grave and old for his years, and doesn't seem to care much for pleasure and admiration, as most men would after a youth like his, for he has had a hard time, I believe.

626
00:56:57,130 --> 00:57:04,330
For a wonder, he consented to come when Mrs. Langdon asked him, and I flew off at once to tell you and secure you for tonight."

627
00:57:04,330 --> 00:57:06,090
"A thousand thanks.

628
00:57:06,090 --> 00:57:12,340
I meant to rest, for Mamma frets about my being so gay; but she won't object to a quiet evening with you.

629
00:57:12,340 --> 00:57:13,700
What shall we wear?"

630
00:57:13,700 --> 00:57:19,220
And here the conversation branched off on the all-absorbing topic of dress.

631
00:57:19,220 --> 00:57:27,740
When Lillian joined her friend that evening, the hero had already arrived, and, stepping into a recess, she waited to catch a glimpse of him.

632
00:57:27,740 --> 00:57:34,100
Maud was called away, and she was alone when the crowd about the inner room thinned and permitted young Talbot to be seen.

633
00:57:34,100 --> 00:57:45,580
Well for Lillian that no one observed her at that moment, for she grew pale and sank into a chair, exclaiming below her breath, "It is Paulâ€”my Paul!"

634
00:57:45,580 --> 00:57:51,600
She recognized him instantly, in spite of increased height, a dark moustache, and martial bearing.

635
00:57:51,600 --> 00:58:04,390
It was Paul, older, graver, handsomer, but still "her Paul," as she called him, with a flush of pride and delight as she watched him, and felt that of all there she knew him best and loved him most.

636
00:58:04,390 --> 00:58:12,780
For the childish affection still existed, and this discovery added a tinge of romance that made it doubly dangerous as well as doubly pleasant.

637
00:58:12,780 --> 00:58:14,040
Will he know me?

638
00:58:14,040 --> 00:58:30,180
she thought, glancing at a mirror which reflected a slender figure with bright hair, white arms, and brilliant eyes; a graceful little head, proudly carried, and a sweet mouth, just then very charming, as it smiled till pearly teeth shone between the ruddy lips.

639
00:58:30,180 --> 00:58:43,210
I'm glad I'm not ugly, and I hope he'll like me, she thought, as she smoothed the golden ripples on her forehead, settled her sash, and shook out the folds of her airy dress in a flutter of girlish excitement.

640
00:58:43,210 --> 00:58:58,030
"I'll pretend not to know him, when we meet, and see what he will do," she said, with a wicked sense of power; for being forewarned she was forearmed, and, fearing no betrayal of surprise on her own part, was eager to enjoy any of which he might be guilty.

641
00:58:58,030 --> 00:59:03,860
Leaving her nook, she joined a group of young friends and held herself prepared for the meeting.

642
00:59:03,860 --> 00:59:10,820
Presently she saw Maud and Mrs. Langdon approaching, evidently intent on presenting the hero to the heiress.

643
00:59:10,820 --> 00:59:14,520
"Mr. Talbot, Miss Trevlyn," said the lady.

644
00:59:14,520 --> 00:59:22,360
And looking up with a well-assumed air of indifference, Lillian returned the gentleman's bow with her eyes fixed full upon his face.

645
00:59:22,360 --> 00:59:29,860
Not a feature of that face changed, and so severely unconscious of any recognition was it that the girl was bewildered.

646
00:59:29,860 --> 00:59:45,940
For a moment she fancied she had been mistaken in his identity, and a pang of disappointment troubled her; but as he moved a chair for Maud, she saw on the one ungloved hand a little scar which she remembered well, for he received it in saving her from a dangerous fall.

647
00:59:45,940 --> 00:59:53,340
At the sight all the happy past rose before her, and if her telltale eyes had not been averted they would have betrayed her.

648
00:59:53,340 --> 01:00:02,380
A sudden flush of maidenly shame dyed her cheek as she remembered that last ride, and the childish confidences then interchanged.

649
01:00:02,380 --> 01:00:10,850
This Helen was the little sweetheart whose picture he wore, and now, in spite of all obstacles, he had won both fortune and ladylove.

650
01:00:10,850 --> 01:00:19,450
The sound of his voice recalled her thoughts, and glancing up she met the deep eyes fixed on her with the same steady look they used to wear.

651
01:00:19,450 --> 01:00:28,480
He had addressed her, but what he said she knew not, beyond a vague idea that it was some slight allusion to the music going on in the next room.

652
01:00:28,480 --> 01:00:43,480
With a smile which would serve for an answer to almost any remark, she hastily plunged into conversation with a composure that did her credit in the eyes of her friends, who stood in awe of the young hero, for all were but just out.

653
01:00:43,480 --> 01:00:51,110
"Mr. Talbot hardly needs an introduction here, for his name is well-known among us, though this is perhaps his first visit to England?"

654
01:00:51,110 --> 01:00:57,160
she said, flattering herself that this artful speech would entrap him into the reply she wanted.

655
01:00:57,160 --> 01:01:09,380
With a slight frown, as if the allusion to his adventure rather annoyed him, and a smile that puzzled all but Lillian, he answered very simply, "It is not my first visit to this hospitable island.

656
01:01:09,380 --> 01:01:14,110
I was here a few years ago, for a short time, and left with regret."

657
01:01:14,110 --> 01:01:16,170
"Then you have old friends here?"

658
01:01:16,170 --> 01:01:18,640
And Lillian watched him as she spoke.

659
01:01:18,640 --> 01:01:20,040
"I had.

660
01:01:20,040 --> 01:01:26,780
They had doubtless forgotten me now," he said, with a sudden shadow marring the tranquillity of his face.

661
01:01:26,780 --> 01:01:28,430
"Why doubt them?

662
01:01:28,430 --> 01:01:31,390
If they were true friends, they will not forget."

663
01:01:31,390 --> 01:01:40,780
The words were uttered impulsively, almost warmly, but Talbot made no response, except a polite inclination and an abrupt change in the conversation.

664
01:01:40,780 --> 01:01:43,440
"That remains to be proved.

665
01:01:43,440 --> 01:01:45,280
Do you sing, Miss Trevlyn?"

666
01:01:45,280 --> 01:01:46,400
"A little."

667
01:01:46,400 --> 01:01:49,370
And Lillian's tone was both cold and proud.

668
01:01:49,370 --> 01:01:56,340
"A great deal, and very charmingly," added Maud, who took pride in her friend's gifts both of voice and beauty.

669
01:01:56,340 --> 01:01:59,710
"Come, dear, there are so few of us you will sing, I know.

670
01:01:59,710 --> 01:02:02,810
Mamma desired me to ask you when Edith had done."

671
01:02:02,810 --> 01:02:07,420
To her surprise Lillian complied, and allowed Talbot to lead her to the instrument.

672
01:02:07,420 --> 01:02:18,460
Still hoping to win some sign of recognition from him, the girl chose an air he taught her and sang it with a spirit and skill that surprised the listeners who possessed no key to her mood.

673
01:02:18,460 --> 01:02:27,020
At the last verse her voice suddenly faltered, but Talbot took up the song and carried her safely through it with his well-tuned voice.

674
01:02:27,020 --> 01:02:28,730
"You know the air then?"

675
01:02:28,730 --> 01:02:33,410
she said in a low tone, as a hum of commendation followed the music.

676
01:02:33,410 --> 01:02:42,180
"All Italians sing it, though few do it like yourself," he answered quietly, restoring the fan he had held while standing beside her.

677
01:02:42,180 --> 01:02:43,860
Provoking boy!

678
01:02:43,860 --> 01:02:45,170
why won't he know me?

679
01:02:45,170 --> 01:02:45,950
thought Lillian.

680
01:02:45,950 --> 01:02:49,990
And her tone was almost petulant as she refused to sing again.

681
01:02:49,990 --> 01:02:58,040
Talbot offered his arm and led her to a seat, behind which stood a little statuette of a child holding a fawn by a daisy chain.

682
01:02:58,040 --> 01:02:59,650
"Pretty, isn't it?"

683
01:02:59,650 --> 01:03:04,140
she said, as he paused to look at it instead of taking the chair before her.

684
01:03:04,140 --> 01:03:10,240
"I used to enjoy modeling tiny deer and hinds in wax, as well as making daisy chains.

685
01:03:10,240 --> 01:03:14,920
Is sculpture among the many accomplishments which rumor tells us you possess?"

686
01:03:14,920 --> 01:03:16,230
"No.

687
01:03:16,230 --> 01:03:24,820
Those who, like me, have their own fortunes to mold find time for little else," he answered gravely, still examining the marble group.

688
01:03:24,820 --> 01:03:39,340
Lillian broke her fan with an angry flirt, for she was tired of her trial, and wished she had openly greeted him at the beginning; feeling now how pleasant it would have been to sit chatting of old times, while her friends dared hardly address him at all.

689
01:03:39,340 --> 01:03:46,340
She was on the point of calling him by his former name, when the remembrance of what he had been arrested the words on her lips.

690
01:03:46,340 --> 01:03:52,820
He was proud; would he not dread to have it known that, in his days of adversity, he had been a servant?

691
01:03:52,820 --> 01:03:58,490
For if she betrayed her knowledge of his past, she would be forced to tell where and how that knowledge was gained.

692
01:03:58,490 --> 01:04:05,980
No, better wait till they met alone, she thought; he would thank her for her delicacy, and she could easily explain her motive.

693
01:04:05,980 --> 01:04:14,110
He evidently wished to seem a stranger, for once she caught a gleam of the old, mirthful mischief in his eye, as she glanced up unexpectedly.

694
01:04:14,110 --> 01:04:19,760
He did remember her, she was sure, yet was trying her, perhaps, as she tried him.

695
01:04:19,760 --> 01:04:23,350
Well, she would stand the test and enjoy the joke by-and-by.

696
01:04:23,350 --> 01:04:36,590
With this fancy in her head she assumed a gracious air and chatted away in her most charming style, feeling both gay and excited, so anxious was she to please, and so glad to recover her early friend.

697
01:04:36,590 --> 01:04:46,150
A naughty whim seized her as her eye fell on a portfolio of classical engravings which someone had left in disorder on a table near her.

698
01:04:46,150 --> 01:04:56,120
Tossing them over she asked his opinion of several, and then handed him one in which Helen of Troy was represented as giving her hand to the irresistible Paris.

699
01:04:56,120 --> 01:05:00,440
"Do you think her worth so much bloodshed, and deserving so much praise?"

700
01:05:00,440 --> 01:05:07,220
she asked, vainly trying to conceal the significant smile that would break loose on her lips and sparkle in her eyes.

701
01:05:07,220 --> 01:05:21,740
Talbot laughed the short, boyish laugh so familiar to her ears, as he glanced from the picture to the arch questioner, and answered in a tone that made her heart beat with a nameless pain and pleasure, so full of suppressed ardor was it:

702
01:05:21,740 --> 01:05:22,840
"Yes!

703
01:05:22,840 --> 01:05:27,100
'All for love or the world well lost' is a saying I heartily agree to.

704
01:05:27,100 --> 01:05:32,760
La belle Helene is my favorite heroine, and I regard Paris as the most enviable of men."

705
01:05:32,760 --> 01:05:34,740
"I should like to see her."

706
01:05:34,740 --> 01:05:43,770
The wish broke from Lillian involuntarily, and she was too much confused to turn it off by any general expression of interest in the classical lady.

707
01:05:43,770 --> 01:05:58,280
"You may sometime," answered Talbot, with an air of amusement; adding, as if to relieve her, "I have a poetical belief that all the lovely women of history or romance will meet, and know, and love each other in some charming hereafter."

708
01:05:58,280 --> 01:06:06,760
"But I'm no heroine and no beauty, so I shall never enter your poetical paradise," said Lillian, with a pretty affectation of regret.

709
01:06:06,760 --> 01:06:12,770
"Some women are beauties without knowing it, and the heroines of romances never given to the world.

710
01:06:12,770 --> 01:06:15,350
I think you and Helen will yet meet, Miss Trevlyn."

711
01:06:15,350 --> 01:06:28,130
As he spoke, Mrs. Langdon beckoned, and he left her pondering over his last words, and conscious of a secret satisfaction in his implied promise that she should see his betrothed.

712
01:06:28,130 --> 01:06:29,720
"How do you like him?"

713
01:06:29,720 --> 01:06:32,640
whispered Maud, slipping into the empty chair.

714
01:06:32,640 --> 01:06:39,330
"Very well," was the composed reply; for Lillian enjoyed her little mystery too much to spoil it yet.

715
01:06:39,330 --> 01:06:40,920
"What did you say to him?

716
01:06:40,920 --> 01:06:46,590
I longed to hear, for you seemed to enjoy yourselves very much, but I didn't like to be a marplot."

717
01:06:46,590 --> 01:06:56,330
Lillian repeated a part of the conversation, and Maud professed to be consumed with jealousy at the impression her friend had evidently made.

718
01:06:56,330 --> 01:07:06,320
"It is folly to try to win the hero, for he is already won, you know," answered Lillian, shutting the cover on the pictured Helen with a sudden motion as if glad to extinguish her.

719
01:07:06,320 --> 01:07:16,280
"Oh dear, no; Mrs. Langdon just told Mamma that she was mistaken about their being engaged; for she asked him and he shook his head, saying Helen was his ward."

720
01:07:16,280 --> 01:07:19,940
"But that is absurd, for he's only a boy himself.

721
01:07:19,940 --> 01:07:21,780
It's very odd, isn't it?

722
01:07:21,780 --> 01:07:24,860
Never mind, I shall soon know all about it."

723
01:07:24,860 --> 01:07:26,040
"How?"

724
01:07:26,040 --> 01:07:29,210
cried Maud, amazed at Lillian's assured manner.

725
01:07:29,210 --> 01:07:32,990
"Wait a day or two and, I'll tell you a romance in return for yours.

726
01:07:32,990 --> 01:07:36,370
Your mother beckons to me, so I know Hester has come.

727
01:07:36,370 --> 01:07:37,480
Good night.

728
01:07:37,480 --> 01:07:39,310
I've had a charming time."

729
01:07:39,310 --> 01:07:43,020
And with this tantalizing adieu, Lillian slipped away.

730
01:07:43,020 --> 01:07:52,800
Hester was waiting in the carriage, but as Lillian appeared, Talbot put aside the footman and handed her in, saying very low, in the well-remembered tone:

731
01:07:52,800 --> 01:07:55,680
"Good night, my little mistress."

732
