01:08:14,490 --> 01:08:15,820
Chapter 6

737
01:08:15,820 --> 01:08:17,200
FAIR HELEN

738
01:08:17,200 --> 01:08:23,230
To no one but her mother and Hester did Lillian confide the discovery she had made.

739
01:08:23,230 --> 01:08:31,660
None of the former servants but old Bedford remained with them, and till Paul chose to renew the old friendship it was best to remain silent.

740
01:08:31,660 --> 01:08:42,580
Great was the surprise and delight of our lady and Hester at the good fortune of their protege, and many the conjectures as to how he would explain his hasty flight.

741
01:08:42,580 --> 01:08:47,240
"You will go and see him, won't you, Mamma, or at least inquire about him?"

742
01:08:47,240 --> 01:08:54,390
said Lillian, eager to assure the wanderer of a welcome, for those few words of his had satisfied her entirely.

743
01:08:54,390 --> 01:09:00,390
"No, dear, it is for him to seek us, and till he does, I shall make no sign.

744
01:09:00,390 --> 01:09:06,250
He knows where we are, and if he chooses he can renew the acquaintance so strangely broken off.

745
01:09:06,250 --> 01:09:17,840
Be patient, and above all things remember, Lillian, that you are no longer a child," replied my lady, rather disturbed by her daughter's enthusiastic praises of Paul.

746
01:09:17,840 --> 01:09:23,790
"I wish I was, for then I might act as I feel, and not be afraid of shocking the proprieties."

747
01:09:23,790 --> 01:09:26,870
And Lillian went to bed to dream of her hero.

748
01:09:26,870 --> 01:09:35,570
For three days she stayed at home, expecting Paul, but he did not come, and she went out for her usual ride in the Park, hoping to meet him.

749
01:09:35,570 --> 01:09:44,290
An elderly groom now rode behind her, and she surveyed him with extreme disgust, as she remembered the handsome lad who had once filled that place.

750
01:09:44,290 --> 01:09:53,480
Nowhere did Paul appear, but in the Ladies' Mile she passed an elegant brougham in which sat a very lovely girl and a mild old lady.

751
01:09:53,480 --> 01:09:57,580
"That is Talbot's fiancee," said Maud Churchill, who had joined her.

752
01:09:57,580 --> 01:09:59,390
"Isn't she beautiful?"

753
01:09:59,390 --> 01:10:07,780
"Not at allâ€”yes, very," was Lillian's somewhat peculiar reply, for jealousy and truth had a conflict just then.

754
01:10:07,780 --> 01:10:15,490
"He's so perfectly absorbed and devoted that I am sure that story is true, so adieu to our hopes," laughed Maud.

755
01:10:15,490 --> 01:10:17,070
"Did you have any?

756
01:10:17,070 --> 01:10:18,790
Good-bye, I must go."

757
01:10:18,790 --> 01:10:23,440
And Lillian rode home at a pace which caused the stout groom great distress.

758
01:10:23,440 --> 01:10:26,050
"Mamma, I've seen Paul's betrothed!"

759
01:10:26,050 --> 01:10:29,120
she cried, running into her mother's boudoir.

760
01:10:29,120 --> 01:10:38,250
"And I have seen Paul himself," replied my lady, with a warning look, for there he stood, with half-extended hand, as if waiting to be acknowledged.

761
01:10:38,250 --> 01:10:49,800
Lillian forgot her embarrassment in her pleasure, and made him an elaborate curtsy, saying, with a half-merry, half-reproachful glance, "Mr. Talbot is welcome in whatever guise he appears."

762
01:10:49,800 --> 01:10:57,970
"I choose to appear as Paul, then, and offer you a seat, Miss Lillian," he said, assuming as much of his boyish manner as he could.

763
01:10:57,970 --> 01:11:05,920
Lillian took it and tried to feel at ease, but the difference between the lad she remembered and the man she now saw was too great to be forgotten.

764
01:11:05,920 --> 01:11:18,080
"Now tell us your adventures, and why you vanished away so mysteriously four years ago," she said, with a touch of the childish imperiousness in her voice, though her frank eyes fell before his.

765
01:11:18,080 --> 01:11:23,760
"I was about to do so when you appeared with news concerning my cousin," he began.

766
01:11:23,760 --> 01:11:24,920
"Your cousin!"

767
01:11:24,920 --> 01:11:26,640
exclaimed Lillian.

768
01:11:26,640 --> 01:11:29,910
"Yes, Helen's mother and my own were sisters.

769
01:11:29,910 --> 01:11:34,650
Both married Englishmen, both died young, leaving us to care for each other.

770
01:11:34,650 --> 01:11:40,090
We were like a brother and sister, and always together till I left her to serve Colonel Daventry.

771
01:11:40,090 --> 01:11:46,110
The death of the old priest to whom I entrusted her recalled me to Genoa, for I was then her only guardian.

772
01:11:46,110 --> 01:11:55,760
I meant to have taken leave of you, my lady, properly, but the consequences of that foolish trick of mine frightened me away in the most unmannerly fashion."

773
01:11:55,760 --> 01:12:03,980
"Ah, it was you, then, in the state chamber; I always thought so," and Lady Trevlyn drew a long breath of relief.

774
01:12:03,980 --> 01:12:11,990
"Yes, I heard it whispered among the servants that the room was haunted, and I felt a wish to prove the truth of the story and my own courage.

775
01:12:11,990 --> 01:12:20,160
Hester locked me in, for fear of my sleepwalking; but I lowered myself by a rope and then climbed in at the closet window of the state chamber.

776
01:12:20,160 --> 01:12:27,860
When you came, my lady, I thought it was Hester, and slipped into the bed, meaning to give her a fright in return for her turning the key on me.

777
01:12:27,860 --> 01:12:34,190
But when your cry showed me what I had done, I was filled with remorse, and escaped as quickly and quietly as possible.

778
01:12:34,190 --> 01:12:42,290
I should have asked pardon before; I do now, most humbly, my lady, for it was sacrilege to play pranks there."

779
01:12:42,290 --> 01:12:51,800
During the first part of his story Paul's manner had been frank and composed, but in telling the latter part, his demeanor underwent a curious change.

780
01:12:51,800 --> 01:13:02,170
He fixed his eyes on the ground and spoke as if repeating a lesson, while his color varied, and a half-proud, half-submissive expression replaced the former candid one.

781
01:13:02,170 --> 01:13:16,480
Lillian observed this, and it disturbed her, but my lady took it for shame at his boyish freak and received his confession kindly, granting a free pardon and expressing sincere pleasure at his amended fortunes.

782
01:13:16,480 --> 01:13:31,220
As he listened, Lillian saw him clench his hand hard and knit his brows, assuming the grim look she had often seen, as if trying to steel himself against some importunate emotion or rebellious thought.

783
01:13:31,220 --> 01:13:43,190
"Yes, half my work is done, and I have a home, thanks to my generous benefactor, and I hope to enjoy it well and wisely," he said in a grave tone, as if the fortune had not yet brought him his heart's desire.

784
01:13:43,190 --> 01:13:46,420
"And when is the other half of the work to be accomplished, Paul?

785
01:13:46,420 --> 01:13:48,890
That depends on your cousin, perhaps."

786
01:13:48,890 --> 01:13:54,740
And Lady Trevlyn regarded him with a gleam of womanly curiosity in her melancholy eyes.

787
01:13:54,740 --> 01:13:58,240
"It does, but not in the way you fancy, my lady.

788
01:13:58,240 --> 01:14:01,770
Whatever Helen may be, she is not my fiancee yet, Miss Lillian."

789
01:14:01,770 --> 01:14:11,160
And the shadow lifted as he laughed, looking at the young lady, who was decidedly abashed, in spite of a sense of relief caused by his words.

790
01:14:11,160 --> 01:14:16,510
"I merely accepted the world's report," she said, affecting a nonchalant air.

791
01:14:16,510 --> 01:14:21,430
"The world is a liar, as you will find in time" was his abrupt reply.

792
01:14:21,430 --> 01:14:24,280
"I hope to see this beautiful cousin, Paul.

793
01:14:24,280 --> 01:14:26,940
Will she receive us as old friends of yours?"

794
01:14:26,940 --> 01:14:29,360
"Thanks, not yet, my lady.

795
01:14:29,360 --> 01:14:33,870
She is still too much a stranger here to enjoy new faces, even kind ones.

796
01:14:33,870 --> 01:14:39,510
I have promised perfect rest and freedom for a time, but you shall be the first whom she receives."

797
01:14:39,510 --> 01:14:46,250
Again Lillian detected the secret disquiet which possessed him, and her curiosity was roused.

798
01:14:46,250 --> 01:14:55,280
It piqued her that this Helen felt no desire to meet her and chose to seclude herself, as if regardless of the interest and admiration she excited.

799
01:14:55,280 --> 01:15:00,310
"I will see her in spite of her refusal, for I only caught a glimpse in the Park.

800
01:15:00,310 --> 01:15:06,140
Something is wrong, and I'll discover it, for it evidently worries Paul, and perhaps I can help him."

801
01:15:06,140 --> 01:15:15,610
As this purpose sprang up in the warm but willful heart of the girl, she regained her spirits and was her most charming self while the young man stayed.

802
01:15:15,610 --> 01:15:26,840
They talked of many things in a pleasant, confidential manner, though when Lillian recalled that hour, she was surprised to find how little Paul had really told them of his past life or future plans.

803
01:15:26,840 --> 01:15:42,620
It was agreed among them to say nothing of their former relations, except to old Bedford, who was discretion itself, but to appear to the world as new-made friendsâ€”thus avoiding unpleasant and unnecessary explanations which would only excite gossip.

804
01:15:42,620 --> 01:15:59,650
My lady asked him to dine, but he had business out of town and declined, taking his leave with a lingering look, which made Lillian steal away to study her face in the mirror and wonder if she looked her best, for in Paul's eyes she had read undisguised admiration.

805
01:15:59,650 --> 01:16:07,060
Lady Trevlyn went to her room to rest, leaving the girl free to ride, drive, or amuse herself as she liked.

806
01:16:07,060 --> 01:16:15,880
As if fearing her courage would fail if she delayed, Lillian ordered the carriage, and, bidding Hester mount guard over her, she drove away to St.

807
01:16:15,880 --> 01:16:17,100
John's Wood.

808
01:16:17,100 --> 01:16:28,110
"Now, Hester, don't lecture or be prim when I tell you that we are going on a frolic," she began, after getting the old woman into an amiable mood by every winning wile she could devise.

809
01:16:28,110 --> 01:16:31,630
"I think you'll like it, and if it's found out I'll take the blame.

810
01:16:31,630 --> 01:16:36,080
There is some mystery about Paul's cousin, and I'm going to find it out."

811
01:16:36,080 --> 01:16:38,270
"Bless you, child, how?"

812
01:16:38,270 --> 01:16:43,160
"She lives alone here, is seldom seen, and won't go anywhere or receive anyone.

813
01:16:43,160 --> 01:16:45,440
That's not natural in a pretty girl.

814
01:16:45,440 --> 01:16:51,070
Paul won't talk about her, and, though he's fond of her, he always looks grave and grim when I ask questions.

815
01:16:51,070 --> 01:16:53,590
That's provoking, and I won't hear it.

816
01:16:53,590 --> 01:17:06,780
Maud is engaged to Raleigh, you know; well, he confided to her that he and a friend had found out where Helen was, had gone to the next villa, which is empty, and under pretense of looking at it got a peep at the girl in her garden.

817
01:17:06,780 --> 01:17:08,720
I'm going to do the same."

818
01:17:08,720 --> 01:17:11,060
"And what am I to do?"

819
01:17:11,060 --> 01:17:17,610
asked Hester, secretly relishing the prank, for she was dying with curiosity to behold Paul's cousin.

820
01:17:17,610 --> 01:17:21,950
"You are to do the talking with the old woman, and give me a chance to look.

821
01:17:21,950 --> 01:17:26,040
Now say you will, and I'll behave myself like an angel in return."

822
01:17:26,040 --> 01:17:39,220
Hester yielded, after a few discreet scruples, and when they reached Laburnum Lodge played her part so well that Lillian soon managed to stray away into one of the upper rooms which overlooked the neighboring garden.

823
01:17:39,220 --> 01:17:43,200
Helen was there, and with eager eyes the girl scrutinized her.

824
01:17:43,200 --> 01:17:55,690
She was very beautiful, in the classical style; as fair and finely molded as a statue, with magnificent dark hair and eyes, and possessed of that perfect grace which is as effective as beauty.

825
01:17:55,690 --> 01:18:06,180
She was alone, and when first seen was bending over a flower which she caressed and seemed to examine with great interest as she stood a long time motionless before it.

826
01:18:06,180 --> 01:18:18,220
Then she began to pace slowly around and around the little grass plot, her hands hanging loosely clasped before her, and her eyes fixed on vacancy as if absorbed in thought.

827
01:18:18,220 --> 01:18:24,870
But as the first effect of her beauty passed away, Lillian found something peculiar about her.

828
01:18:24,870 --> 01:18:38,330
It was not the somewhat foreign dress and ornaments she wore; it was in her face, her movements, and the tone of her voice, for as she walked she sang a low, monotonous song, as if unconsciously.

829
01:18:38,330 --> 01:18:51,300
Lillian watched her keenly, marking the aimless motions of the little hands, the apathy of the lovely face, and the mirthless accent of the voice; but most of all the vacant fixture of the great dark eyes.

830
01:18:51,300 --> 01:18:58,670
Around and around she went, with an elastic step and a mechanical regularity wearisome to witness.

831
01:18:58,670 --> 01:19:00,720
What is the matter with her?

832
01:19:00,720 --> 01:19:07,130
thought Lillian anxiously, as this painful impression increased with every scrutiny of the unconscious girl.

833
01:19:07,130 --> 01:19:13,950
So abashed was she that Hester's call was unheard, and Hester was unseen as she came and stood beside her.

834
01:19:13,950 --> 01:19:25,100
Both looked a moment, and as they looked an old lady came from the house and led Helen in, still murmuring her monotonous song and moving her hands as if to catch and hold the sunshine.

835
01:19:25,100 --> 01:19:27,650
"Poor dear, poor dear.

836
01:19:27,650 --> 01:19:35,140
No wonder Paul turns sad and won't talk of her, and that she don't see anyone," sighed Hester pitifully.

837
01:19:35,140 --> 01:19:36,930
"What is it?

838
01:19:36,930 --> 01:19:41,320
I see, but don't understand," whispered Lillian.

839
01:19:41,320 --> 01:19:47,730
"She's an innocent, deary, an idiot, though that's a hard word for a pretty creature like her."

840
01:19:47,730 --> 01:19:49,150
"How terrible!

841
01:19:49,150 --> 01:19:52,240
Come away, Hester, and never breathe to anyone what we have seen."

842
01:19:52,240 --> 01:20:01,930
And with a shudder and sense of pain and pity lying heavy at her heart, she hurried away, feeling doubly guilty in the discovery of this affliction.

843
01:20:01,930 --> 01:20:12,510
The thought of it haunted her continually; the memory of the lonely girl gave her no peace; and a consciousness of deceit burdened her unspeakably, especially in Paul's presence.

844
01:20:12,510 --> 01:20:21,880
This lasted for a week, then Lillian resolved to confess, hoping that when he found she knew the truth he would let her share his cross and help to lighten it.

845
01:20:21,880 --> 01:20:30,150
Waiting her opportunity, she seized a moment when her mother was absent, and with her usual frankness spoke out impetuously.

846
01:20:30,150 --> 01:20:34,900
"Paul, I've done wrong, and I can have no peace till I am pardoned.

847
01:20:34,900 --> 01:20:36,860
I have seen Helen."

848
01:20:36,860 --> 01:20:39,240
"Where, when, and how?"

849
01:20:39,240 --> 01:20:41,770
he asked, looking disturbed and yet relieved.

850
01:20:41,770 --> 01:20:52,420
She told him rapidly, and as she ended she looked up at him with her sweet face, so full of pity, shame, and grief it would have been impossible to deny her anything.

851
01:20:54,040 --> 01:20:57,080
"Can you forgive me for discovering this affliction?"

852
01:20:57,080 --> 01:21:03,770
"I think I could forgive you a far greater fault, Lillian," he answered, in a tone that said many things.

853
01:21:03,770 --> 01:21:10,270
"But deceit is so mean, so dishonorable and contemptible, how can you so easily pardon it in me?"

854
01:21:10,270 --> 01:21:16,160
she asked, quite overcome by this forgiveness, granted without any reproach.

855
01:21:16,160 --> 01:21:20,120
"Then you would find it hard to pardon such a thing in another?"

856
01:21:20,120 --> 01:21:23,390
he said, with the expression that always puzzled her.

857
01:21:23,390 --> 01:21:28,730
"Yes, it would be hard; but in those I loved, I could forgive much for love's sake."

858
01:21:28,730 --> 01:21:34,170
With a sudden gesture he took her hand saying, impulsively, "How little changed you are!

859
01:21:34,170 --> 01:21:37,720
Do you remember that last ride of ours nearly five years ago?"

860
01:21:37,720 --> 01:21:41,090
"Yes, Paul," she answered, with averted eyes.

861
01:21:41,090 --> 01:21:43,160
"And what we talked of?"

862
01:21:43,160 --> 01:21:46,680
"A part of that childish gossip I remember well."

863
01:21:46,680 --> 01:21:48,320
"Which part?"

864
01:21:48,320 --> 01:21:51,320
"The pretty little romance you told me."

865
01:21:51,320 --> 01:21:57,170
And Lillian looked up now, longing to ask if Helen's childhood had been blighted like her youth.

866
01:21:57,170 --> 01:22:06,280
Paul dropped her hand as if he, read her thoughts, and his own hand went involuntarily toward his breast, betraying that the locket still hung there.

867
01:22:06,280 --> 01:22:07,950
"What did I say?"

868
01:22:07,950 --> 01:22:11,070
he asked, smiling at her sudden shyness.

869
01:22:11,070 --> 01:22:15,510
"You vowed you'd win and wed your fair little lady-love if you lived."

870
01:22:15,510 --> 01:22:19,950
"And so I will," he cried, with sudden fire in his eyes.

871
01:22:19,950 --> 01:22:21,610
"What, marry her?"

872
01:22:21,610 --> 01:22:23,520
"Aye, that I will."

873
01:22:23,520 --> 01:22:33,110
"Oh Paul, will you tie yourself for life to aâ€”" The word died on her lips, but a gesture of repugnance finished the speech.

874
01:22:33,110 --> 01:22:34,520
"A what?"

875
01:22:34,520 --> 01:22:36,370
he demanded, excitedly.

876
01:22:36,370 --> 01:22:43,900
"An innocent, one bereft of reason," stammered Lillian, entirely forgetting herself in her interest for him.

877
01:22:43,900 --> 01:22:45,590
"Of whom do you speak?"

878
01:22:45,590 --> 01:22:48,100
asked Paul, looking utterly bewildered,

879
01:22:48,100 --> 01:22:49,900
"Of poor Helen."

880
01:22:49,900 --> 01:22:52,890
"Good heavens, who told you that base lie?"

881
01:22:52,890 --> 01:22:56,190
And his voice deepened with indignant pain.

882
01:22:56,190 --> 01:23:02,440
"I saw her, you did not deny her affliction; Hester said so, and I believed it.

883
01:23:02,440 --> 01:23:04,620
Have I wronged her, Paul?"

884
01:23:04,620 --> 01:23:06,740
"Yes, cruelly.

885
01:23:06,740 --> 01:23:09,810
She is blind, but no idiot, thank God."

886
01:23:09,810 --> 01:23:24,200
There was such earnestness in his voice, such reproach in his words, and such ardor in his eye, that Lillian's pride gave way, and with a broken entreaty for pardon, she covered up her face, weeping the bitterest tears she ever shed.

887
01:23:24,200 --> 01:23:31,000
For in that moment, and the sharp pang it brought her, she felt how much she loved Paul and how hard it was to lose him.

888
01:23:31,000 --> 01:23:41,490
The childish affection had blossomed into a woman's passion, and in a few short weeks had passed through many phases of jealousy, hope, despair, and self-delusion.

889
01:23:41,490 --> 01:23:55,030
The joy she felt on seeing him again, the pride she took in him, the disgust Helen caused her, the relief she had not dared to own even to herself, when she fancied fate had put an insurmountable barrier between Paul and his cousin,

890
01:23:55,030 --> 01:24:09,790
the despair at finding it only a fancy, and the anguish of hearing him declare his unshaken purpose to marry his first loveâ€”all these conflicting emotions had led to this hard moment, and now self-control deserted her in her need.

891
01:24:09,790 --> 01:24:21,500
In spite of her efforts the passionate tears would have their way, though Paul soothed her with assurances of entire forgiveness, promises of Helen's friendship, and every gentle device he could imagine.

892
01:24:21,500 --> 01:24:32,950
She commanded herself at last by a strong effort, murmuring eagerly as she shrank from the hand that put back her fallen hair, and the face so full of tender sympathy bending over her:

893
01:24:32,950 --> 01:24:36,820
"I am so grieved and ashamed at what I have said and done.

894
01:24:36,820 --> 01:24:38,480
I shall never dare to see Helen.

895
01:24:38,480 --> 01:24:40,450
Forgive me, and forget this folly.

896
01:24:40,450 --> 01:24:48,950
I'm sad and heavyhearted just now; it's the anniversary of Papa's death, and Mamma always suffers so much at such times that I get nervous."

897
01:24:48,950 --> 01:24:50,580
"It is your birthday also.

898
01:24:50,580 --> 01:24:56,070
I remembered it, and ventured to bring a little token in return for the one you gave me long ago.

899
01:24:56,070 --> 01:25:00,570
This is a talisman, and tomorrow I will tell you the legend concerning it.

900
01:25:00,570 --> 01:25:03,950
Wear it for my sake, and God bless you, dear."

901
01:25:03,950 --> 01:25:13,340
The last words were whispered hurriedly; Lillian saw the glitter of an antique ring, felt the touch of bearded lips on her hand, and Paul was gone.

902
01:25:13,340 --> 01:25:22,060
But as he left the house he set his teeth, examining low to himself, "Yes, tomorrow there will be an end of this!

903
01:25:22,060 --> 01:25:25,030
We must risk everything and abide the consequences now.

904
01:25:25,030 --> 01:25:28,260
I'll have no more torment for any of us."

