Chapter 7

910
01:25:46,940 --> 01:25:48,630
THE SECRET KEY

911
01:25:48,630 --> 01:25:51,140
"Is Lady Trevlyn at home, Bedford?"

912
01:25:51,140 --> 01:25:59,290
asked Paul, as he presented himself at an early hour next day, wearing the keen, stern expression which made him look ten years older than he was.

913
01:25:59,290 --> 01:26:03,670
"No, sir, my lady and Miss Lillian went down to the Hall last night."

914
01:26:03,670 --> 01:26:05,480
"No ill news, I hope?"

915
01:26:05,480 --> 01:26:09,570
And the young man's eye kindled as if he felt a crisis at hand.

916
01:26:09,570 --> 01:26:11,500
"Not that I heard, sir.

917
01:26:11,500 --> 01:26:21,410
Miss Lillian took one of her sudden whims and would have gone alone, if my lady hadn't given in much against her will, this being a time when she is better away from the place."

918
01:26:21,410 --> 01:26:23,900
"Did they leave no message for me?"

919
01:26:23,900 --> 01:26:25,010
"Yes, sir.

920
01:26:25,010 --> 01:26:27,320
Will you step in and read the note at your ease.

921
01:26:27,320 --> 01:26:30,740
We are in sad confusion, but this room is in order."

922
01:26:30,740 --> 01:26:35,290
Leading the way to Lillian's boudoir, the man presented the note and retired.

923
01:26:35,290 --> 01:26:42,230
A few hasty lines from my lady, regretting the necessity of this abrupt departure, yet giving no reason for it,

924
01:26:42,230 --> 01:26:52,950
hoping they might meet next season, but making no allusion to seeing him at the Hall, desiring Lillian's thanks and regards, but closing with no hint of Helen, except compliments.

925
01:26:52,950 --> 01:27:03,010
Paul smiled as he threw it into the fire, saying to himself, "Poor lady, she thinks she has escaped the danger by flying, and Lillian tries to hide her trouble from me.

926
01:27:03,010 --> 01:27:04,480
Tender little heart!

927
01:27:04,480 --> 01:27:06,640
I'll comfort it without delay."

928
01:27:06,640 --> 01:27:11,410
He sat looking about the dainty room still full of tokens of her presence.

929
01:27:11,410 --> 01:27:28,060
The piano stood open with a song he liked upon the rack; a bit of embroidery, whose progress he had often watched, lay in her basket with the little thimble near it; there was a strew of papers on the writing table, torn notes, scraps of drawing, and ball cards;

930
01:27:28,060 --> 01:27:35,200
a pearl-colored glove lay on the floor; and in the grate the faded flowers he had brought two days before.

931
01:27:35,200 --> 01:27:42,390
As his eye roved to and fro, he seemed to enjoy some happy dream, broken too soon by the sound of servants shutting up the house.

932
01:27:42,390 --> 01:27:48,300
He arose but lingered near the table, as if longing to search for some forgotten hint of himself.

933
01:27:48,300 --> 01:27:53,550
"No, there has been enough lock picking and stealthy work; I'll do no more for her sake.

934
01:27:53,550 --> 01:27:56,510
This theft will harm no one and tell no tales."

935
01:27:56,510 --> 01:27:59,580
And snatching up the glove, Paul departed.

936
01:27:59,580 --> 01:28:01,770
"Helen, the time has come.

937
01:28:01,770 --> 01:28:02,720
Are you ready?"

938
01:28:02,720 --> 01:28:05,390
he asked, entering her room an hour later.

939
01:28:05,390 --> 01:28:06,730
"I am ready."

940
01:28:06,730 --> 01:28:13,430
And rising, she stretched her hand to him with a proud expression, contrasting painfully with her helpless gesture.

941
01:28:13,430 --> 01:28:15,890
"They have gone to the Hall, and we must follow.

942
01:28:15,890 --> 01:28:24,150
It is useless to wait longer; we gain nothing by it, and the claim must stand on such proof as we have, or fall for want of that one link.

943
01:28:24,150 --> 01:28:25,890
I am tired of disguise.

944
01:28:25,890 --> 01:28:30,160
I want to be myself and enjoy what I have won, unless I lose it all."

945
01:28:30,160 --> 01:28:37,040
"Paul, whatever happens, remember we cling together and share good or evil fortune as we always have done.

946
01:28:37,040 --> 01:28:40,700
I am a burden, but I cannot live without you, for you are my world.

947
01:28:40,700 --> 01:28:42,560
Do not desert me."

948
01:28:42,560 --> 01:28:47,570
She groped her way to him and clung to his strong arm as if it was her only stay.

949
01:28:47,570 --> 01:29:00,350
Paul drew her close, saying wistfully, as he caressed the beautiful sightless face leaning on his shoulder, "Mia cara, would it break your heart, if at the last hour I gave up all and let the word remain unspoken?

950
01:29:00,350 --> 01:29:05,880
My courage fails me, and in spite of the hard past I would gladly leave them in peace."

951
01:29:05,880 --> 01:29:08,960
"No, no, you shall not give it up!"

952
01:29:08,960 --> 01:29:15,770
cried Helen almost fiercely, while the slumbering fire of her southern nature flashed into her face.

953
01:29:15,770 --> 01:29:22,000
"You have waited so long, worked so hard, suffered so much, you must not lose your reward.

954
01:29:22,000 --> 01:29:24,910
You promised, and you must keep the promise."

955
01:29:24,910 --> 01:29:30,340
"But it is so beautiful, so noble to forgive, and return a blessing for a curse.

956
01:29:30,340 --> 01:29:34,100
Let us bury the old feud, and right the old wrong in a new way.

957
01:29:34,100 --> 01:29:38,910
Those two are so blameless, it is cruel to visit the sins of the dead on their innocent heads.

958
01:29:38,910 --> 01:29:46,680
My lady has suffered enough already, and Lillian is so young, so happy, so unfit to meet a storm like this.

959
01:29:46,680 --> 01:29:50,220
Oh, Helen, mercy is more divine than justice."

960
01:29:50,220 --> 01:29:57,330
Something moved Paul deeply, and Helen seemed about to yield, when the name of Lillian wrought a subtle change in her.

961
01:29:57,330 --> 01:30:09,560
The color died out of her face, her black eyes burned with a gloomy fire, and her voice was relentless as she answered, while her frail hands held him fast, "I will not let you give it up.

962
01:30:09,560 --> 01:30:16,350
We are as innocent as they; we have suffered more; and we deserve our rights, for we have no sin to expiate.

963
01:30:16,350 --> 01:30:20,420
Go on, Paul, and forget the sentimental folly that unmans you."

964
01:30:20,420 --> 01:30:23,890
Something in her words seemed to sting or wound him.

965
01:30:23,890 --> 01:30:29,370
His face darkened, and he put her away, saying briefly, "Let it be so then.

966
01:30:29,370 --> 01:30:31,860
In an hour we must go."

967
01:30:31,860 --> 01:30:38,320
On the evening of the same day, Lady Trevlyn and her daughter sat together in the octagon room at the Hall.

968
01:30:38,320 --> 01:30:53,720
Twilight was falling and candles were not yet brought, but a cheery fire blazed in the wide chimney, filling the apartment with a ruddy glow, turning Lillian's bright hair to gold and lending a tinge of color to my lady's pallid cheeks.

969
01:30:53,720 --> 01:31:03,210
The girl sat on a low lounging chair before the fire, her head on her hands, her eyes on the red embers, her thoughtsâ€”where?

970
01:31:03,210 --> 01:31:14,020
My lady lay on her couch, a little in the shadow, regarding her daughter with an anxious air, for over the young face a somber change had passed which filled her with disquiet.

971
01:31:14,020 --> 01:31:23,520
"You are out of spirits, love," she said at last, breaking the long silence, as Lillian gave an unconscious sigh and leaned wearily into the depths of the chair.

972
01:31:23,520 --> 01:31:25,890
"Yes, Mamma, a little."

973
01:31:25,890 --> 01:31:27,140
"What is it?

974
01:31:27,140 --> 01:31:28,230
Are you ill?"

975
01:31:28,230 --> 01:31:32,200
"No, Mamma; I think London gaiety is rather too much for me.

976
01:31:32,200 --> 01:31:35,860
I'm too young for it, as you often say, and I've found it out."

977
01:31:35,860 --> 01:31:41,360
"Then it is only weariness that makes you so pale and grave, and so bent on coming back here?"

978
01:31:41,360 --> 01:31:48,640
Lillian was the soul of truth, and with a moment's hesitation answered slowly, "Not that alone, Mamma.

979
01:31:48,640 --> 01:31:50,850
I'm worried about other things.

980
01:31:50,850 --> 01:31:53,380
Don't ask me what, please."

981
01:31:53,380 --> 01:31:55,130
"But I must ask.

982
01:31:55,130 --> 01:31:57,070
Tell me, child, what things?

983
01:31:57,070 --> 01:31:58,430
Have you seen any one?

984
01:31:58,430 --> 01:32:02,480
Had letters, or been annoyed in any way aboutâ€”anything?"

985
01:32:02,480 --> 01:32:09,770
My lady spoke with sudden energy and rose on her arm, eyeing the girl with unmistakable suspicion and excitement.

986
01:32:09,770 --> 01:32:19,380
"No, Mamma, it's only a foolish trouble of my own," answered Lillian, with a glance of surprise and a shamefaced look as the words reluctantly left her lips.

987
01:32:19,380 --> 01:32:22,450
"Ah, a love trouble, nothing more?

988
01:32:22,450 --> 01:32:23,950
Thank God for that!"

989
01:32:23,950 --> 01:32:27,320
And my lady sank back as if a load was off her mind.

990
01:32:27,320 --> 01:32:31,710
"Tell me all, my darling; there is no confidante like a mother."

991
01:32:31,710 --> 01:32:38,350
"You are very kind, and perhaps you can cure my folly if I tell it, and yet I am ashamed," murmured the girl.

992
01:32:38,350 --> 01:32:48,380
Then yielding to an irresistible impulse to ask help and sympathy, she added, in an almost inaudible tone, "I came away to escape from Paul."

993
01:32:48,380 --> 01:32:50,700
"Because he loves you, Lillian?"

994
01:32:50,700 --> 01:32:53,890
asked my lady, with a frown and a half smile.

995
01:32:53,890 --> 01:32:56,800
"Because he does not love me, Mamma."

996
01:32:56,800 --> 01:33:05,830
And the poor girl hid her burning cheeks in her hands, as if overwhelmed with maidenly shame at the implied confession of her own affection.

997
01:33:05,830 --> 01:33:07,970
"My child, how is this?

998
01:33:07,970 --> 01:33:13,730
I cannot but be glad that he does not love you; yet it fills me with grief to see that this pains you.

999
01:33:13,730 --> 01:33:15,780
He is not a mate for you, Lillian.

1000
01:33:15,780 --> 01:33:22,020
Remember this, and forget the transient regard that has sprung up from that early intimacy of yours."

1001
01:33:22,020 --> 01:33:34,930
"He is wellborn, and now my equal in fortune, and oh, so much my superior in all gifts of mind and heart," sighed the girl, still with hidden face, for tears were dropping through her slender fingers.

1002
01:33:34,930 --> 01:33:41,650
"It may be, but there is a mystery about him; and I have a vague dislike to him in spite of all that has passed.

1003
01:33:41,650 --> 01:33:44,490
But, darling, are you sure he does not care for you?

1004
01:33:44,490 --> 01:33:54,140
I fancied I read a different story in his face, and when you begged to leave town so suddenly, I believed that you had seen this also, and kindly wished to spare him any pain."

1005
01:33:54,140 --> 01:33:57,450
"It was to spare myself.

1006
01:33:57,450 --> 01:34:01,330
Oh, Mamma, he loves Helen, and will marry her although she is blind.

1007
01:34:01,330 --> 01:34:08,910
He told me this, with a look I could not doubt, and so I came away to hide my sorrow," sobbed poor Lillian in despair.

1008
01:34:08,910 --> 01:34:24,520
Lady Trevlyn went to her and, laying the bright head on her motherly bosom, said soothingly as she caressed it, "My little girl, it is too soon for you to know these troubles, and I am punished for yielding to your entreaties for a peep at the gay world.

1009
01:34:24,520 --> 01:34:30,000
It is now too late to spare you this; you have had your wish and must pay its price, dear.

1010
01:34:30,000 --> 01:34:33,550
But, Lillian, call pride to aid you, and conquer this fruitless love.

1011
01:34:33,550 --> 01:34:40,160
It cannot be very deep as yet, for you have known Paul, the man, too short a time to be hopelessly enamored.

1012
01:34:40,160 --> 01:34:48,630
Remember, there are others, better, braver, more worthy of you; that life is long, and full of pleasure yet untried."

1013
01:34:48,630 --> 01:34:50,880
"Have no fears for me, Mamma.

1014
01:34:50,880 --> 01:34:54,560
I'll not disgrace you or myself by any sentimental folly.

1015
01:34:54,560 --> 01:34:58,380
I do love Paul, but I can conquer it, and I will.

1016
01:34:58,380 --> 01:35:02,730
Give me a little time, and you shall see me quite myself again."

1017
01:35:02,730 --> 01:35:11,590
Lillian lifted her head with an air of proud resolve that satisfied her mother, and with a grateful kiss stole away to ease her full heart alone.

1018
01:35:11,590 --> 01:35:23,680
As she disappeared Lady Trevlyn drew a long breath and, clasping her hands with a gesture of thanksgiving, murmured to herself in an accent of relief, "Only a love sorrow!

1019
01:35:23,680 --> 01:35:26,310
I feared it was some new terror like the old one.

1020
01:35:26,310 --> 01:35:37,130
Seventeen years of silence, seventeen years of secret dread and remorse for me," she said, pacing the room with tightly locked hands and eyes full of unspeakable anguish.

1021
01:35:37,130 --> 01:35:38,860
"Oh, Richard, Richard!

1022
01:35:38,860 --> 01:35:44,970
I forgave you so long ago, and surely I have expiated my innocent offense by these years of suffering!

1023
01:35:44,970 --> 01:35:49,050
For her sake I did it, and for her sake I still keep dumb.

1024
01:35:49,050 --> 01:35:53,640
God knows I ask nothing for myself but rest and oblivion by your side."

1025
01:35:53,640 --> 01:35:56,720
Half an hour later, Paul stood at the hall door.

1026
01:35:56,720 --> 01:36:03,290
It was ajar, for the family had returned unexpectedly, as was evident from the open doors and empty halls.

1027
01:36:03,290 --> 01:36:08,130
Entering unseen, he ascended to the room my lady usually occupied.

1028
01:36:08,130 --> 01:36:18,610
The fire burned low, Lillian's chair was empty, and my lady was asleep, as if lulled by the sighing winds without and the deep silence that reigned within.

1029
01:36:18,610 --> 01:36:30,090
Paul stood regarding her with a great pity softening his face as he marked the sunken eyes, pallid cheeks, locks too early gray, and restless lips muttering in dreams.

1030
01:36:30,090 --> 01:36:34,830
"I wish I could spare her this," he sighed, stooping to wake her with a word.

1031
01:36:34,830 --> 01:36:46,830
But he did not speak, for, suddenly clutching the chain about her neck, she seemed to struggle with some invisible foe and beat it off, muttering audibly as she clenched her thin hands on the golden case.

1032
01:36:46,830 --> 01:36:57,940
Paul leaned and listened as if the first word had turned him to stone, till the paroxysm had passed, and with a heavy sigh my lady sank into a calmer sleep.

1033
01:36:57,940 --> 01:37:11,030
Then, with a quick glance over his shoulder, Paul skillfully opened the locket, drew out the silver key, replaced it with one from the piano close by, and stole from the house noiselessly as he had entered it.

1034
01:37:11,030 --> 01:37:18,700
That night, in the darkest hour before the dawn, a figure went gliding through the shadowy Park to its most solitary corner.

1035
01:37:18,700 --> 01:37:23,040
Here stood the tomb of the Trevlyns, and here the figure paused.

1036
01:37:23,040 --> 01:37:32,710
A dull spark of light woke in its hand, there was a clank of bars, the creak of rusty hinges, then light and figure both seemed swallowed up.

1037
01:37:32,710 --> 01:37:43,620
Standing in the tomb where the air was close and heavy, the pale glimmer of the lantern showed piles of moldering coffins in the niches, and everywhere lay tokens of decay and death.

1038
01:37:43,620 --> 01:37:55,850
The man drew his hat lower over his eyes, pulled the muffler closer about his mouth, and surveyed the spot with an undaunted aspect, though the beating of his heart was heard in the deep silence.

1039
01:37:55,850 --> 01:38:03,580
Nearest the door stood a long casket covered with black velvet and richly decorated with silver ornaments, tarnished now.

1040
01:38:03,580 --> 01:38:15,980
The Trevlyns had been a stalwart race, and the last sleeper brought there had evidently been of goodly stature, for the modern coffin was as ponderous as the great oaken beds where lay the bones of generations.

1041
01:38:15,980 --> 01:38:33,680
Lifting the lantern, the intruder brushed the dust from the shield-shaped plate, read the name RICHARD TREVLYN and a date, and, as if satisfied, placed a key in the lock, half-raised the lid, and, averting his head that he might not see the ruin seventeen long years had made,

1042
01:38:33,680 --> 01:38:40,020
he laid his hand on the dead breast and from the folded shroud drew a mildewed paper.

1043
01:38:40,020 --> 01:38:51,270
One glance sufficed, the casket was relocked, the door rebarred, the light extinguished, and the man vanished like a ghost in the darkness of the wild October night.

