Chapter 8

1049
01:39:09,500 --> 01:39:10,810
WHICH?

1050
01:39:10,810 --> 01:39:12,920
"A Gentleman, my lady."

1051
01:39:12,920 --> 01:39:24,810
Taking a card from the silver salver on which the servant offered it, Lady Trevlyn read, "Paul Talbot," and below the name these penciled words, "I beseech you to see me."

1052
01:39:24,810 --> 01:39:27,650
Lillian stood beside her and saw the line.

1053
01:39:27,650 --> 01:39:36,450
Their eyes met, and in the girl's face was such a sudden glow of hope, and love, and longing, that the mother could not doubt or disappoint her wish.

1054
01:39:36,450 --> 01:39:39,060
"I will see him," she said.

1055
01:39:39,060 --> 01:39:41,120
"Oh, Mamma, how kind you are!"

1056
01:39:41,120 --> 01:39:46,480
cried the girl with a passionate embrace, adding breathlessly, "He did not ask for me.

1057
01:39:46,480 --> 01:39:47,950
I cannot see him yet.

1058
01:39:47,950 --> 01:39:53,720
I'll hide in the alcove, and can appear or run away as I like when we know why he comes."

1059
01:39:53,720 --> 01:40:03,380
They were in the library, for, knowing Lillian's fondness for the room which held no dark memories for her, my lady conquered her dislike and often sat there.

1060
01:40:03,380 --> 01:40:12,130
As she spoke, the girl glided into the deep recess of a bay window and drew the heavy curtains just as Paul's step sounded at the door.

1061
01:40:12,130 --> 01:40:18,130
Hiding her agitation with a woman's skill, my lady rose with outstretched hand to welcome him.

1062
01:40:18,130 --> 01:40:27,680
He bowed but did not take the hand, saying, in a voice of grave respect in which was audible an undertone of strong emotion, "Pardon me, Lady Trevlyn.

1063
01:40:27,680 --> 01:40:32,720
Hear what I have to say; and then if you offer me your hand, I shall gratefully receive it."

1064
01:40:32,720 --> 01:40:46,470
She glanced at him, and saw that he was very pale, that his eye glittered with suppressed excitement, and his whole manner was that of a man who had nerved himself up to the performance of a difficult but intensely interesting task.

1065
01:40:46,470 --> 01:40:57,420
Fancying these signs of agitation only natural in a young lover coming to woo, my lady smiled, reseated herself, and calmly answered, "I will listen patiently.

1066
01:40:57,420 --> 01:41:01,100
Speak freely, Paul, and remember I am an old friend."

1067
01:41:01,100 --> 01:41:03,300
"I wish I could forget it.

1068
01:41:03,300 --> 01:41:18,450
Then my task would be easier," he murmured in a voice of mingled regret and resolution, as he leaned on a tall chair opposite and wiped his damp forehead, with a look of such deep compassion that her heart sank with a nameless fear.

1069
01:41:18,450 --> 01:41:24,920
"I must tell you a long story, and ask your forgiveness for the offenses I committed against you when a boy.

1070
01:41:24,920 --> 01:41:29,160
A mistaken sense of duty guided me, and I obeyed it blindly.

1071
01:41:29,160 --> 01:41:33,000
Now I see my error and regret it," he said earnestly.

1072
01:41:33,000 --> 01:41:40,420
"Go on," replied my lady, while the vague dread grew stronger, and she braced her nerves as for some approaching shock.

1073
01:41:40,420 --> 01:41:47,330
She forgot Lillian, forgot everything but the strange aspect of the man before her, and the words to which she listened like a statue.

1074
01:41:47,330 --> 01:41:55,200
Still standing pale and steady, Paul spoke rapidly, while his eyes were full of mingled sternness, pity, and remorse.

1075
01:41:55,200 --> 01:42:01,810
"Twenty years ago, an English gentleman met a friend in a little Italian town, where he had married a beautiful wife.

1076
01:42:01,810 --> 01:42:11,930
The wife had a sister as lovely as herself, and the young man, during that brief stay, loved and married herâ€”in a very private manner, lest his father should disinherit him.

1077
01:42:11,930 --> 01:42:19,180
A few months passed, and the Englishman was called home to take possession of his title and estates, the father being dead.

1078
01:42:19,180 --> 01:42:22,990
He went alone, promising to send for the wife when all was ready.

1079
01:42:22,990 --> 01:42:29,770
He told no one of his marriage, meaning to surprise his English friends by producing the lovely woman unexpectedly.

1080
01:42:29,770 --> 01:42:41,890
He had been in England but a short time when he received a letter from the old priest of the Italian town, saying the cholera had swept through it, carrying off half its inhabitants, his wife and friend among others.

1081
01:42:41,890 --> 01:42:49,700
This blow prostrated the young man, and when he recovered he hid his grief, shut himself up in his country house, and tried to forget.

1082
01:42:49,700 --> 01:42:54,560
Accident threw in his way another lovely woman, and he married again.

1083
01:42:54,560 --> 01:43:02,180
Before the first year was out, the friend whom he supposed was dead appeared, and told him that his wife still lived, and had borne him a child.

1084
01:43:02,180 --> 01:43:08,820
In the terror and confusion of the plague, the priest had mistaken one sister for the other, as the elder did die."

1085
01:43:08,820 --> 01:43:11,700
"Yes, yes, I know; go on!"

1086
01:43:11,700 --> 01:43:16,730
gasped my lady, with white lips, and eyes that never left the narrator's face.

1087
01:43:16,730 --> 01:43:23,310
"This friend had met with misfortune after flying from the doomed village with the surviving sister.

1088
01:43:23,310 --> 01:43:30,820
They had waited long for letters, had written, and, when no answer came, had been delayed by illness and poverty from reaching England.

1089
01:43:30,820 --> 01:43:41,550
At this time the child was born, and the friend, urged by the wife and his own interest, came here, learned that Sir Richard was married, and hurried to him in much distress.

1090
01:43:41,550 --> 01:43:45,180
We can imagine the grief and horror of the unhappy man.

1091
01:43:45,180 --> 01:43:57,710
In that interview the friend promised to leave all to Sir Richard, to preserve the secret till some means of relief could be found; and with this promise he returned, to guard and comfort the forsaken wife.

1092
01:43:57,710 --> 01:44:08,960
Sir Richard wrote the truth to Lady Trevlyn, meaning to kill himself, as the only way of escape from the terrible situation between two women, both so beloved, both so innocently wronged.

1093
01:44:08,960 --> 01:44:15,190
The pistol lay ready, but death came without its aid, and Sir Richard was spared the sin of suicide."

1094
01:44:15,190 --> 01:44:22,660
Paul paused for breath, but Lady Trevlyn motioned him to go on, still sitting rigid and white as the marble image near her.

1095
01:44:22,660 --> 01:44:25,850
"The friend only lived to reach home and tell the story.

1096
01:44:25,850 --> 01:44:33,460
It killed the wife, and she died, imploring the old priest to see her child righted and its father's name secured to it.

1097
01:44:33,460 --> 01:44:38,200
He promised; but he was poor, the child was a frail baby, and he waited.

1098
01:44:38,200 --> 01:44:48,710
Years passed, and when the child was old enough to ask for its parents and demand its due, the proofs of the marriage were lost, and nothing remained but a ring, a bit of writing, and the name.

1099
01:44:48,710 --> 01:44:57,740
The priest was very old, had neither friends, money, nor proofs to help him; but I was strong and hopeful, and though a mere boy I resolved to do the work.

1100
01:44:57,740 --> 01:45:14,470
I made my way to England, to Trevlyn Hall, and by various stratagems (among which, I am ashamed to say, were false keys and feigned sleepwalking) I collected many proofs, but nothing which would satisfy a court, for no one but you knew where Sir Richard's confession was.

1101
01:45:14,470 --> 01:45:24,870
I searched every nook and corner of the Hall, but in vain, and began to despair, when news of the death of Father Cosmo recalled me to Italy; for Helen was left to my care then.

1102
01:45:24,870 --> 01:45:36,380
The old man had faithfully recorded the facts and left witnesses to prove the truth of his story; but for four years I never used it, never made any effort to secure the title or estates."

1103
01:45:36,380 --> 01:45:38,050
"Why not?"

1104
01:45:38,050 --> 01:45:42,650
breathed my lady in a faint whisper, as hope suddenly revived.

1105
01:45:42,650 --> 01:45:47,620
"Because I was grateful," and for the first time Paul's voice faltered.

1106
01:45:47,620 --> 01:45:50,610
"I was a stranger, and you took me in.

1107
01:45:50,610 --> 01:45:56,170
I never could forget that, nor tie many kindnesses bestowed upon the friendless boy.

1108
01:45:56,170 --> 01:46:02,740
This afflicted me, even while I was acting a false part, and when I was away my heart failed me.

1109
01:46:02,740 --> 01:46:11,850
But Helen gave me no peace; for my sake, she urged me to keep the vow made to that poor mother, and threatened to tell the story herself.

1110
01:46:11,850 --> 01:46:18,890
Talbot's benefaction left me no excuse for delaying longer, and I came to finish the hardest task I can ever undertake.

1111
01:46:18,890 --> 01:46:28,440
I feared that a long dispute would follow any appeal to law, and meant to appeal first to you, but fate befriended me, and the last proof was found."

1112
01:46:28,440 --> 01:46:29,770
"Found!

1113
01:46:29,770 --> 01:46:30,560
Where?"

1114
01:46:30,560 --> 01:46:33,500
cried Lady Trevlyn, springing up aghast.

1115
01:46:33,500 --> 01:46:39,590
"In Sir Richard's coffin, where you hid it, not daring to destroy, yet fearing to keep it."

1116
01:46:39,590 --> 01:46:41,840
"Who has betrayed me?"

1117
01:46:41,840 --> 01:46:47,230
And her eye glanced wildly about the room, as if she feared to see some spectral accuser.

1118
01:46:47,230 --> 01:46:49,090
"Your own lips, my lady.

1119
01:46:49,090 --> 01:46:51,610
Last night I came to speak of this.

1120
01:46:51,610 --> 01:47:00,700
You lay asleep, and in some troubled dream spoke of the paper, safe in its writer's keeping, and your strange treasure here, the key of which you guarded day and night.

1121
01:47:00,700 --> 01:47:02,219
I divined the truth.

1122
01:47:02,219 --> 01:47:11,970
Remembering Hester's stories, I took the key from your helpless hand, found the paper on Sir Richard's dead breast, and now demand that you confess your part in this tragedy."

1123
01:47:11,970 --> 01:47:13,790
"I do, I do!

1124
01:47:13,790 --> 01:47:18,930
I confess, I yield, I relinquish everything, and ask pity only for my child."

1125
01:47:18,930 --> 01:47:31,450
Lady Trevlyn fell upon her knees before him, with a submissive gesture, but imploring eyes, for, amid the wreck of womanly pride and worldly fortune, the mother's heart still clung to its idol.

1126
01:47:31,450 --> 01:47:33,700
"Who should pity her, if not I?

1127
01:47:33,700 --> 01:47:41,560
God knows I would have spared her this blow if I could; but Helen would not keep silent, and I was driven to finish what I had begun.

1128
01:47:41,560 --> 01:47:45,070
Tell Lillian this, and do not let her hate me."

1129
01:47:45,070 --> 01:48:00,690
As Paul spoke, tenderly, eagerly, the curtain parted, and Lillian appeared, trembling with the excitement of that interview, but conscious of only one emotion as she threw herself into his arms, crying in a tone of passionate delight, "Brother!

1130
01:48:00,690 --> 01:48:01,580
Brother!

1131
01:48:01,580 --> 01:48:03,000
Now I may love you!"

1132
01:48:03,000 --> 01:48:07,870
Paul held her close, and for a moment forgot everything but the joy of that moment.

1133
01:48:07,870 --> 01:48:22,560
Lillian spoke first, looking up through tears of tenderness, her little hand laid caressingly against his cheek, as she whispered with sudden bloom in her own, "Now I know why I loved you so well, and now I can see you marry Helen without breaking my heart.

1134
01:48:22,560 --> 01:48:26,620
Oh, Paul, you are still mine, and I care for nothing else."

1135
01:48:26,620 --> 01:48:29,230
"But, Lillian, I am not your brother."

1136
01:48:29,230 --> 01:48:31,750
"Then, in heaven's name, who are you?"

1137
01:48:31,750 --> 01:48:34,760
she cried, tearing herself from his arms.

1138
01:48:34,760 --> 01:48:36,860
"Your lover, dear!"

1139
01:48:36,860 --> 01:48:38,780
"Who, then, is the heir?"

1140
01:48:38,780 --> 01:48:44,570
demanded Lady Trevlyn, springing up, as Lillian turned to seek shelter with her mother.

1141
01:48:44,570 --> 01:48:46,570
"I am."

1142
01:48:46,570 --> 01:48:54,170
Helen spoke, and Helen stood on the threshold of the door, with a hard, haughty look upon her beautiful face.

1143
01:48:54,170 --> 01:48:58,260
"You told your story badly, Paul," she said, in a bitter tone.

1144
01:48:58,260 --> 01:49:07,210
"You forgot me, forgot my affliction, my loneliness, my wrongs, and the natural desire of a child to clear her mother's honor and claim her father's name.

1145
01:49:07,210 --> 01:49:09,750
I am Sir Richard's eldest daughter.

1146
01:49:09,750 --> 01:49:15,590
I can prove my birth, and I demand my right with his own words to sustain me."

1147
01:49:15,590 --> 01:49:24,230
She paused, but no one spoke; and with a slight tremor in her proud voice, she added, "Paul has done the work; he shall have the reward.

1148
01:49:24,230 --> 01:49:26,390
I only want my father's name.

1149
01:49:26,390 --> 01:49:29,500
Title and fortune are nothing to one like me.

1150
01:49:29,500 --> 01:49:36,640
I coveted and claimed them that I might give them to you, Paul, my one friend, always, so tender and so true."

1151
01:49:36,640 --> 01:49:40,320
"I'll have none of it," he answered, almost fiercely.

1152
01:49:40,320 --> 01:49:42,810
"I have kept my promise, and am free.

1153
01:49:42,810 --> 01:49:47,140
You chose to claim your own, although I offered all I had to buy your silence.

1154
01:49:47,140 --> 01:49:50,820
It is yours by rightâ€”take it, and enjoy it if you can.

1155
01:49:50,820 --> 01:49:53,890
I'll have no reward for work like this."

1156
01:49:53,890 --> 01:49:58,860
He turned from her with a look that would have stricken her to the heart could she have seen it.

1157
01:49:58,860 --> 01:50:11,430
She felt it, and it seemed to augment some secret anguish, for she pressed her hands against her bosom with an expression of deep suffering, exclaiming passionately, "Yes, I will keep it, since I am to lose all else.

1158
01:50:11,430 --> 01:50:12,870
I am tired of pity.

1159
01:50:12,870 --> 01:50:15,240
Power is sweet, and I will use it.

1160
01:50:15,240 --> 01:50:22,740
Go, Paul, and be happy if you can, with a nameless wife, and the world's compassion or contempt to sting your pride."

1161
01:50:22,740 --> 01:50:25,230
"Oh, Lillian, where shall we go?

1162
01:50:25,230 --> 01:50:28,450
This is no longer our home, but who will receive us now?"

1163
01:50:28,450 --> 01:50:38,730
cried Lady Trevlyn, in a tone of despair, for her spirit was utterly broken by the thought of the shame and sorrow in store for this beloved and innocent child.

1164
01:50:38,730 --> 01:50:39,830
"I will."

1165
01:50:39,830 --> 01:50:44,350
And Paul's face shone with a love and loyalty they could not doubt.

1166
01:50:44,350 --> 01:50:49,570
"My lady, you gave me a home when I was homeless; now let me pay my debt.

1167
01:50:49,570 --> 01:50:56,590
Lillian, I have loved you from the time when, a romantic boy, I wore your little picture in my breast, and vowed to win you if I lived.

1168
01:50:56,590 --> 01:51:03,660
I dared not speak before, but now, when other hearts may be shut against you, mine stands wide open to welcome you.

1169
01:51:03,660 --> 01:51:04,880
Come, both.

1170
01:51:04,880 --> 01:51:08,870
Let me protect and cherish you, and so atone for the sorrow I have brought you."

1171
01:51:08,870 --> 01:51:20,780
It was impossible to resist the sincere urgency of his voice, the tender reverence of his manner, as he took the two forlorn yet innocent creatures into the shelter of his strength and love.

1172
01:51:20,780 --> 01:51:29,680
They clung to him instinctively, feeling that there still remained to them one staunch friend whom adversity could not estrange.

1173
01:51:29,680 --> 01:51:39,560
An eloquent silence fell upon the room, broken only by sobs, grateful whispers, and the voiceless vows that lovers plight with eyes, and hands, and tender lips.

1174
01:51:39,560 --> 01:51:51,360
Helen was forgotten, till Lillian, whose elastic spirit threw off sorrow as a flower sheds the rain, looked up to thank Paul, with smiles as well as tears, and saw the lonely figure in the shadow.

1175
01:51:51,360 --> 01:52:00,830
Her attitude was full of pathetic significance; she still stood on the threshold, for no one had welcomed her, and in the strange room she knew not where to go;

1176
01:52:00,830 --> 01:52:12,430
her hands were clasped before her face, as if those sightless eyes had seen the joy she could not share, and at her feet lay the time-stained paper that gave her a barren title, but no love.

1177
01:52:12,430 --> 01:52:28,620
Had Lillian known how sharp a conflict between passion and pride, jealousy and generosity, was going on in that young heart, she could not have spoken in a tone of truer pity or sincerer goodwill than that in which she softly said, "Poor girl!

1178
01:52:28,620 --> 01:52:33,740
We must not forget her, for, with all her wealth, she is poor compared to us.

1179
01:52:33,740 --> 01:52:38,560
We both had one father, and should love each other in spite of this misfortune.

1180
01:52:38,560 --> 01:52:41,970
Helen, may I call you sister?"

1181
01:52:41,970 --> 01:52:43,620
"Not yet.

1182
01:52:43,620 --> 01:52:45,660
Wait till I deserve it."

1183
01:52:45,660 --> 01:53:01,470
As if that sweet voice had kindled an answering spark of nobleness in her own heart, Helen's face changed beautifully, as she tore the paper to shreds, saying in a glad, impetuous tone, while the white flakes fluttered from her hands, "I, too, can be generous.

1184
01:53:01,470 --> 01:53:02,870
I, too, can forgive.

1185
01:53:02,870 --> 01:53:04,510
I bury the sad past.

1186
01:53:04,510 --> 01:53:05,200
See!

1187
01:53:05,200 --> 01:53:12,340
I yield my claim, I destroy my proofs, I promise eternal silence, and keep 'Paul's cousin' for my only title.

1188
01:53:12,340 --> 01:53:15,440
Yes, you are happy, for you love one another!"

1189
01:53:15,440 --> 01:53:18,180
she cried, with a sudden passion of tears.

1190
01:53:18,180 --> 01:53:23,640
"Oh, forgive me, pity me, and take me in, for I am all alone and in the dark!"

1191
01:53:23,640 --> 01:53:34,100
There could be but one reply to an appeal like that, and they gave it, as they welcomed her with words that sealed a household league of mutual secrecy and sacrifice.

1192
01:53:34,100 --> 01:53:48,880
They were happy, for the world never knew the hidden tie that bound them so faithfully together, never learned how well the old prophecy had been fulfilled, or guessed what a tragedy of life and death the silver key unlocked.

